02:36.674 --> 02:40.610
       Hi! Clark Sparkman here, 
       welcoming you all        
       to Sly Base Earth,       

02:40.612 --> 02:43.913
   an airport where the flights 
   are out of this world.       

02:43.915 --> 02:47.683
        And  <i>Celebrity Heat</i>     
        <i>is blasting off!</i>        

02:47.685 --> 02:50.786
    <i>Three years ago,</i>            
    <i>rash billionaire daredevil,</i> 
    <i>Sly Baron,</i>                  

02:50.788 --> 02:55.457
    <i>vowed to make space tourism</i> 
    <i>a reality.</i>                  

02:55.459 --> 03:00.261
 Today, his lucky passengers    
 are boldly going where         
 none of them have gone before. 

03:01.529 --> 03:04.030
        <i>No, not Delaware!</i>       

03:04.032 --> 03:05.131
              <i>Space!</i>            

03:05.133 --> 03:07.666
     <i>A trip around the Moon!</i>    

03:07.668 --> 03:10.935
    <i>And they'll travel in style</i> 
    <i>on</i> Sly Star One,            

03:10.937 --> 03:13.137
   <i>the first space cruise ship.</i> 

03:13.139 --> 03:15.973
         <i>The passengers</i>         
         <i>are pure A-list.</i>       

03:15.975 --> 03:19.142
          <i>Celebrated Astronaut,</i> 
          <i>Shannon Lucas.</i>        

03:19.144 --> 03:22.478
     <i>Retired legends, Zip Elvin</i> 
     <i>and Colt Steelcase.</i>        

03:22.480 --> 03:26.515
          <i>And football star,</i>    
          <i>Uvinious Botango,</i>     
          <i>a.k.a. U-Boat.</i>        

03:26.517 --> 03:29.217
 <i>Superstars going to the stars!</i> 

03:29.219 --> 03:32.286
    But wait, what about        
    the average guy or gal?     

03:32.288 --> 03:35.188
    <i>Didn't Sly promise to make</i>  
    <i>space available to anyone?</i>  

03:35.190 --> 03:37.290
      Yeah, what about us?      

03:38.325 --> 03:40.292
    Hold on                     
    to your boosters, folks,    

03:40.294 --> 03:44.328
       'cause this super cute   
       reporter is about        
       to blow your mind.       

03:44.330 --> 03:46.295
       (PEOPLE CHEERING)        

03:48.798 --> 03:51.199
  Sly created a sensation today 
  when he revealed              

03:51.201 --> 03:55.135
      <i>that he reserved</i>          
      <i>five seats for five</i>       
      <i>lucky lottery winners.</i>    

03:55.137 --> 03:56.903
       Wow!                     
       Who could they be?       

03:57.905 --> 04:00.039
    (DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING)    

04:16.822 --> 04:18.422
          <i>Four teen sleuths</i>     
          <i>and their dog</i>         

04:18.423 --> 04:20.656
      <i>won the "Sly Me To Space"</i> 
      <i>sweepstakes.</i>              

04:20.659 --> 04:23.026
       <i>Luckily, they'll be</i>      
       <i>in the company</i>           
       <i>of space greatness,</i>      

04:23.028 --> 04:25.361
 including me, Clark Sparkman.  

04:25.363 --> 04:29.364
  <i>In T-minus zero, the</i>          
 <i>Celebrity Heat's </i> <i>exclusive</i>    
  <i>intergalactic coverage</i>        

04:29.366 --> 04:31.833
          of the greatest party 
          on Earth.             

04:35.603 --> 04:37.036
        (CROWD CHEERING)        

04:37.038 --> 04:39.038
 How great                      
 are these custom flight suits? 

04:39.040 --> 04:41.106
 I never want to take mine off. 

04:41.108 --> 04:43.875
    I know.                     
    The colors are perfect.     

04:43.877 --> 04:46.277
  And the colors are perfect.   

04:46.279 --> 04:48.245
     And, like, there's pockets 
     for snacks.                

04:48.247 --> 04:49.579
       Ooh, big pockets!        

04:53.783 --> 04:55.416
  State-of-the-art technology.  

04:55.418 --> 04:57.951
 I'm Shannon Lucas.             
 You must be the lucky winners. 

04:57.953 --> 05:00.887
     Hi! You can't imagine      
     how surprised we were      

05:00.889 --> 05:03.122
   to find out we were          
   actually going into space!   

05:03.124 --> 05:06.758
  Oh, I think I can.            
  It was a surprise to me too.  

05:06.760 --> 05:10.228
  The Baron kept it a secret    
  until the very last second.   

05:10.230 --> 05:12.797
     But I guess                
     he's a man of mystery.     

05:12.799 --> 05:13.898
           (LAUGHING)           

05:13.900 --> 05:15.733
 Well, we sure love mysteries.  

05:15.735 --> 05:18.268
   Right, and love solving them 
   even more.                   

05:18.270 --> 05:20.436
         (ALL LAUGHING)         

05:20.438 --> 05:23.739
  -What?                        
  -It's too bad we have to wear 
  these helmets.                

05:23.741 --> 05:25.407
      Talk about hat head.      

05:25.409 --> 05:28.176
   (LAUGHING) I know! Awful.    

05:30.779 --> 05:33.513
 What? I haven't worn mine yet. 

05:34.915 --> 05:36.815
           Oh, sorry.           

05:36.817 --> 05:41.085
    Well, Daphne,               
    your hair is so great,      
    I'd consider not going.     

05:41.087 --> 05:43.153
      Oh, jeepers, thanks!      

05:43.155 --> 05:46.955
   I use a special conditioner, 
   extra bounce.                

05:46.957 --> 05:48.690
          -(HAIR WHIPPING)      
          -(GRUNTING)           

05:49.825 --> 05:51.992
       Well, here we are,       

05:51.994 --> 05:55.328
 about to go into space         
 and we're talking about hair.  

05:55.330 --> 05:57.630
       Hey, what are            
       these lights for?        

05:57.632 --> 05:59.798
      Indicators.               
      Each suit is fitted       

05:59.800 --> 06:02.267
    with every convenience      
    you have here on Earth.     

06:02.269 --> 06:05.903
      (LAUGHING) There's no     
      little boys' room         
      on the ship, Shaggy.      

06:05.905 --> 06:07.571
      You go in the suit.       

06:07.573 --> 06:11.441
  Wow. I really don't have      
  to take this suit off, ever?  

06:11.443 --> 06:12.975
            -Not even for...    
            -Right.             

06:12.977 --> 06:14.943
   I'm guessing that            
   the red light might means    

06:14.945 --> 06:17.612
      you should think about    
      changing out              
      your payload though.      

06:17.614 --> 06:20.514
      Like, dude, we're wearing 
      atomic diapers.           

06:20.516 --> 06:22.649
  The Baron spared no expense.  

06:22.651 --> 06:25.084
       Well, I'm sure           
       Sly can afford it.       

06:25.086 --> 06:28.620
 Besides, all he cares about is 
 over-the-top publicity stunts. 

06:28.622 --> 06:31.856
 I wouldn't be surprised        
 if he made some grand entrance 

06:31.858 --> 06:33.757
       wearing a suit           
       made out of money.       

06:42.099 --> 06:43.966
       (PEOPLE CHEERING)        

06:43.968 --> 06:47.002
 Wow! A suit made out of money. 

06:47.004 --> 06:51.105
     Yes, yes. Cheering for me. 
     You're welcome.            

06:51.107 --> 06:53.674
         Ladies and gentlemen,  
         thanks to me,          

06:53.676 --> 06:58.178
     you're about to experience 
     a life-changing event      
     you'll never forget.       

06:58.180 --> 07:03.349
 A safe and easy way for anyone 
 and everyone to go to space.   

07:03.351 --> 07:05.484
      It will thrill you,       

07:05.486 --> 07:09.487
   especially if you pick up    
   some souvenirs               
   in the Sly Star gift shop.   

07:09.489 --> 07:12.389
     Now, let's blast off!      

07:12.391 --> 07:14.124
        (CROWD CHEERING)        

07:15.693 --> 07:17.460
   (CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)   

07:17.462 --> 07:20.463
      Wow, there's Zip Elvin    
      and Colt Steelcase!       

07:20.465 --> 07:21.697
        Let's go say hi.        

07:21.699 --> 07:23.565
           Hi, Zip.             
           Hi, Colt.            

07:23.567 --> 07:26.067
    (CLEARS THROAT) Fred Jones, 
    reporting for duty.         

07:26.069 --> 07:28.736
         Oh. Hi, Fred.          

07:28.738 --> 07:30.671
           I'm a huge fan!      
           (STAMMERS)           

07:30.673 --> 07:32.472
          A huge fan.           

07:32.474 --> 07:34.874
    Even though you guys        
    landed on the moon          
    years before I was born,    

07:34.876 --> 07:37.009
     you've always been         
     an inspiration to me.      

07:37.011 --> 07:39.544
     -Well, we're not that old. 
     -He can't hear you.        

07:39.546 --> 07:44.248
      -Fred, you need to push   
      the com button on your... 
      -I can't hear you!        

07:44.250 --> 07:46.883
  So, you're probably wearing   
  those diaper things, right?   

07:46.885 --> 07:48.484
        Probably used to them   
        by now, though.         

07:48.486 --> 07:50.185
 I know how it must             
 kind of itch and stuff but...  

07:50.187 --> 07:53.021
         -I think it's so cool. 
         -(GROANING)            

07:53.023 --> 07:57.324
 So, Shannon, do you have       
 our training test scores, yet? 

07:57.326 --> 07:58.858
         Just curious.          

07:58.860 --> 08:00.826
 I'm not obsessed               
 with test scores or anything.  

08:00.828 --> 08:03.028
     I was actually             
     just looking at them.      

08:03.030 --> 08:04.829
       -Wanna know how you did? 
       -Yes!                    

08:04.831 --> 08:06.997
            I mean, sure.       
            Why not?            

08:06.999 --> 08:08.531
        You all passed.         

08:08.533 --> 08:10.332
       But one of you           
       scored high enough       

08:10.334 --> 08:13.068
  to enter the NASA             
  Astronaut Candidate Program.  

08:13.070 --> 08:14.202
            -Nice work...       
            -Thanks.            

08:14.204 --> 08:17.538
          -...Daphne.           
          -Really? Me?          

08:17.540 --> 08:20.040
     Wow! That is so cool!      

08:20.042 --> 08:23.710
      -Have you ever considered 
      being an astronaut?       
      -No, never.               

08:23.712 --> 08:25.812
    I have,                     
    ever since I was a kid.     

08:29.616 --> 08:32.551
 Well, you should.              
 We'll talk later, girlfriend.  

08:32.553 --> 08:35.953
          Okay, sounds great,   
          girlfriend.           

08:35.956 --> 08:39.057
   And maybe you can give me    
   some hair tips. (GIGGLES)    

08:39.058 --> 08:41.392
 Oh, my gosh, I would love to!  

08:41.394 --> 08:43.092
     I'll see you in a bit.     

08:43.095 --> 08:46.328
          Yeah, we'll all talk  
          later then.           

08:47.396 --> 08:49.296
        She is so nice.         

08:49.298 --> 08:52.699
      This is going to be       
      the best trip ever.       

08:52.701 --> 08:55.535
          -What are you doing?  
          -(GROANING)           

08:55.537 --> 08:57.303
        (CROWD CHEERING)        

08:57.305 --> 08:59.537
 MAN: U-Boat! U-Boat! U-Boat... 

09:01.439 --> 09:04.307
           Scoob, it's him!     
           (LAUGHING)           

09:04.309 --> 09:07.243
 Uvinious Botango, the U-Boat.  

09:07.245 --> 09:09.478
     Like, the best             
     football player alive!     

09:11.314 --> 09:13.982
         Okay, everyone needs   
         to calm down.          

09:13.984 --> 09:17.852
    SLY:  <i>All passengers</i>        
     <i>please board</i>               
     <i>and prepare for takeoff.</i>   

09:17.854 --> 09:20.855
 Oh, my gosh!                   
 I've been waiting              
 my whole life for this moment. 

09:20.857 --> 09:22.723
     I can hardly breathe!      

09:23.925 --> 09:26.793
     Okay, let's get going.     

09:28.829 --> 09:31.764
     WOMAN: (ON PA)  <i>T-minus</i>    
     <i>five minutes to launch.</i>    

09:44.911 --> 09:46.444
     (SEATBELT SIGN PINGS)      

09:46.446 --> 09:49.413
 I can't believe                
 Shaggy and Scooby are so calm. 

09:49.415 --> 09:51.448
  They get jumpy on elevators.  

09:51.450 --> 09:53.383
    They have U-Boat fever.     

09:53.385 --> 09:56.052
  -Why do they call him that?   
  -Because he sinks everybody.  

09:56.054 --> 09:57.420
    He's a tackling machine.    

09:57.422 --> 09:59.255
        And he has a line       
        of snack foods.         

09:59.257 --> 10:01.390
          <i>U-Boat Bites!</i>         

10:01.392 --> 10:04.226
  I'll be surprised             
  if Shaggy and Scooby          
  even notice we're in space.   

10:04.228 --> 10:07.462
 Hey, would you like to join us 
 on the bridge for lift-off?    

10:07.464 --> 10:09.630
    Would I? Oh, you have...    

10:09.632 --> 10:11.098
    What do you say, Daphne?    

10:11.100 --> 10:14.201
  Really? Well, sure. Thanks!   

10:14.203 --> 10:15.869
       (VELMA STRAINING)        

10:17.371 --> 10:20.373
 Boy, she sure left in a hurry. 

10:20.375 --> 10:22.108
        Well, at least I have   
        you here, Fred.         

10:22.110 --> 10:25.111
 Hey, Zip, Colt.                
 You guys going to the bridge?  

10:25.113 --> 10:27.879
     -Yeah, but this really...  
     -Great! I'll join you.     

10:30.249 --> 10:32.283
      Wait, I'll come too.      

10:32.285 --> 10:35.753
      Just need to undo         
      these stupid belts.       

10:35.755 --> 10:37.488
      I'd keep those on         
      if you want to live.      

10:37.490 --> 10:39.890
   Ridley,                      
   alien resistance fighter.    

10:44.628 --> 10:46.629
         Wait, really?          
         That's a job?          

10:46.631 --> 10:49.565
    It will be,                 
    when the aliens invade.     

10:49.567 --> 10:51.166
     Velma Dinkley, right?      

10:51.168 --> 10:54.302
    You're one of the teen      
    detectives, Mystery Inc.    

10:54.304 --> 10:56.637
         Clark Sparkman,        
         <i>Celebrity Heat.</i>        

10:59.107 --> 11:01.775
        Mind if I ask you       
        a few questions?        

11:01.777 --> 11:04.277
      You can if you like,      
      but I won't answer.       

11:04.279 --> 11:06.846
   Good call.                   
   TV is a factory of deceit.   

11:12.118 --> 11:13.351
         BOTH: U-Boat!          

11:17.655 --> 11:19.322
      (SCOOBY-DOO GROANS)       

11:19.324 --> 11:21.290
      WOMAN: (ON PA)  <i>T-minus</i>   
      <i>20 seconds to launch.</i>     

11:21.292 --> 11:23.025
    SLY:  <i>Here we go, folks!</i>    

11:23.027 --> 11:27.662
    <i>We're heading to the stars,</i> 
    <i>thanks to me, Sly Baron.</i>    

11:27.664 --> 11:31.632
      MAN: Sly Star One,        
       <i>this is ground control,</i>  
       <i>you are clear to go.</i>     

11:31.634 --> 11:36.136
  WOMAN: (ON PA)  <i>Five, four,</i>   
  <i>three, two. We have ignition.</i> 

11:36.138 --> 11:38.504
        <i>And one. Lift-off.</i>      

11:40.340 --> 11:42.274
       (PEOPLE CHEERING)        

11:50.349 --> 11:53.851
     SLY:  <i>Welcome to space.</i>    

11:53.853 --> 11:56.553
        We did it!              
        High five, guys.        

11:59.456 --> 12:01.790
     SLY:  <i>Ladies and gentlemen,</i>
     <i>we have reached</i>            

12:01.792 --> 12:05.827
      <i>our cruising altitude</i>     
      <i>of one million meters.</i>    

12:05.829 --> 12:07.662
     (SEATBELT SIGN PINGS)      

12:07.664 --> 12:11.499
           <i>Sly Co.'s latest</i>     
           <i>Host Android Marvel,</i> 
           <i>or H.A.M.,</i>           

12:11.501 --> 12:14.068
    <i>is moving through the cabin</i> 
    <i>with refreshments</i>           

12:14.070 --> 12:17.737
      <i>and observational comedy,</i> 
      <i>courtesy of me.</i>           

12:17.739 --> 12:20.873
         <i>You're welcome!</i>        

12:20.875 --> 12:24.509
  <i>You know why moon restaurants</i> 
  <i>always go out of business?</i>    

12:24.511 --> 12:26.077
          <i>No atmosphere.</i>        

12:30.815 --> 12:32.248
       <i>Am I right, people?</i>      

12:33.850 --> 12:35.116
       (VELMA STRAINING)        

12:36.251 --> 12:37.818
        (H.A.M PLAYING          
        STUDIO LAUGHTER)        

12:42.389 --> 12:45.924
    If you need any more        
    buttons pressed,            
    (WHISPERS) I'm your man.    

12:45.926 --> 12:48.993
     Ew. And this sort of stuff 
     works for you?             

12:48.995 --> 12:50.694
         Still not gonna do     
         an interview.          

12:50.696 --> 12:52.529
 I don't watch  <i>Celebrity Heat.</i> 

12:52.531 --> 12:54.364
          -No offense.          
          -None taken.          

12:54.366 --> 12:56.265
   It's my job, not my life.    

12:56.267 --> 12:58.033
          So, want to check out 
          the ship?             

12:58.035 --> 13:00.602
      I'm in.                   
      Strength in numbers.      

13:04.440 --> 13:07.441
        -Look, I think we made  
        a good impression.      
        -(BOTH LAUGHING)        

13:09.377 --> 13:13.279
    <i>-Care for a wet towel, sir?</i> 
   <i> -Out of my way, robot!</i>      

13:13.281 --> 13:15.247
       <i>No peanuts for him.</i>      

13:15.249 --> 13:18.683
      Come on, pal.             
      All this hero talk        
      has made me hungry.       

13:18.685 --> 13:20.518
  Let's go find the snack bar.  

13:20.520 --> 13:22.286
        (BOTH STRAINING)        

13:26.624 --> 13:29.092
     Oh, look at that view!     

13:29.094 --> 13:30.893
          -Been there.          
          -Done that.           

13:30.895 --> 13:32.961
         I never get tired      
         of it, though.         

13:32.963 --> 13:36.264
        How could you?          
        It's... It's...         

13:36.266 --> 13:37.898
            Exactly.            

13:37.900 --> 13:39.032
          What's next?          

13:39.034 --> 13:41.134
     For us, safety check.      

13:41.136 --> 13:44.570
      We got to make sure       
      this billion dollar yacht 
      stays in one piece.       

13:44.572 --> 13:46.304
   Sounds important, I'm in.    

13:48.273 --> 13:50.474
           (GROANING)           

13:50.476 --> 13:52.242
  Aren't you going with them?   

13:52.244 --> 13:54.644
  I have to run diagnostics on  
  the navigation system first.  

13:54.646 --> 13:56.512
    But you go ahead,           
    I'll catch up with you.     

14:00.983 --> 14:05.986
  Shannon, thanks for making me 
  feel like I belong up here.   

14:06.721 --> 14:08.254
            You do!             

14:08.256 --> 14:10.489
      Space needs               
      a lot more Daphnes.       

14:10.491 --> 14:14.159
 I'm just speeding up           
 the process a bit, girlfriend. 
 (GIGGLING)                     

14:14.161 --> 14:18.529
      Okay, thanks, girlfriend. 
      (GIGGLING)                

14:21.099 --> 14:22.365
            (GROWLS)            

14:26.103 --> 14:28.671
  Like, did you see something   
  funny in the window, Scoob?   

14:28.673 --> 14:31.306
           Funny? No.           

14:31.308 --> 14:35.243
        -Me neither.            
        -Phew. Must be          
        our imagination.        

14:35.245 --> 14:40.447
  Like, I once saw a show       
  about a guy that saw gremlins 
  on the outside of his plane.  

14:40.449 --> 14:43.516
     -What happened?            
     -I turned off the TV.      

14:43.518 --> 14:44.917
           Good idea.           

14:57.463 --> 14:58.930
          (CLATTERING)          

15:01.300 --> 15:03.968
     -What was that?            
     -Probably space junk.      

15:03.970 --> 15:07.638
 Since the space age began,     
 we've dumped millions          
 of pieces of trash into orbit. 

15:07.640 --> 15:09.806
       Some weigh more          
       than 6,000 tones.        

15:09.808 --> 15:13.009
  -How do you know all that?    
  -I visited NASA last month.   

15:13.011 --> 15:15.344
           -Research.           
           -Research?           

15:15.346 --> 15:17.145
  You work for  <i>Celebrity Heat.</i> 

15:17.147 --> 15:18.713
          Space junk.           

15:18.715 --> 15:20.648
  That's exactly what           
  the aliens want us to think.  

15:20.650 --> 15:22.716
        Or it's really          
        just space junk.        

15:24.318 --> 15:25.718
  I know what you're thinking.  

15:25.720 --> 15:27.853
    "Ridley. She's just some    
    whacked out alien freak     

15:27.855 --> 15:30.155
       "who's seen one too many 
       sci-fi movies."          

15:30.157 --> 15:33.324
           -Yes, that's exactly 
           what I'm thinking.   
           -Me, too.            

15:33.326 --> 15:36.160
       We are not alone.        

15:36.162 --> 15:40.397
   (LAUGHING)                   
   "We are not alone." Oh...    

15:47.070 --> 15:50.872
     But I've dedicated my life 
     to alien combat training   
     for one simple reason.     

15:54.509 --> 15:56.243
           (GRUNTING)           

16:10.090 --> 16:12.357
         Breakdancing?          

16:12.359 --> 16:15.993
       Combat training.         
       They're out there.       

16:15.995 --> 16:19.329
   And how do you know that?    
   Do you have                  
   any firsthand experience?    

16:19.331 --> 16:21.364
         Yeah, have you ever    
         seen an alien?         

16:21.366 --> 16:23.366
   Have I ever seen an alien?   

16:23.368 --> 16:26.268
   Have I ever seen an alien?   

16:26.270 --> 16:29.137
     Have I ever seen an alien? 
     Ha!                        

16:32.508 --> 16:34.742
         No, I haven't.         

16:34.744 --> 16:37.411
 -But I do have video evidence. 
 -(DEVICE BEEPS)                

16:37.413 --> 16:39.445
    We've been in contact       
    with aliens for decades.    

16:41.214 --> 16:44.416
     Uh... That's a kitten.     

16:44.418 --> 16:46.918
     Oh, sorry, that's not it.  
     Here. Look!                

16:48.353 --> 16:50.287
       <i>Did you see it?</i>          
       <i>It was right there!</i>      

16:50.289 --> 16:51.788
           -(GROWLING)          
           -(STATIC)            

16:58.061 --> 17:00.295
    That's just                 
    the tip of the iceberg.     

17:00.297 --> 17:02.096
          There's more footage. 
          Lots more.            

17:02.098 --> 17:05.232
       And I'll show it to you. 
       Wait here!               

17:05.233 --> 17:08.300
   -And that's our cue to hide. 
   -Way ahead of you.           

17:10.237 --> 17:12.905
    Like, dude,                 
    they have U-Boat Bites.     

17:12.906 --> 17:15.374
   That's U-Boat Nacho Bites!   

17:15.376 --> 17:17.242
  Come on, open up. (PANTING)   

17:17.243 --> 17:19.444
  We're having a snack attack.  

17:19.445 --> 17:21.512
      H.A.M.:  <i>Do you know what</i> 
      <i>my favorite snack is?</i>     

17:28.785 --> 17:32.854
       <i>I don't have one because</i> 
       <i>I cannot digest food.</i>    
       <i>Am I right, people?</i>      

17:37.926 --> 17:39.660
        (H.A.M PLAYING          
        STUDIO LAUGHTER)        

17:40.662 --> 17:41.895
        I don't get it.         

17:43.931 --> 17:46.666
        <i>Are you challenging me,</i> 
        <i>canine life form?</i>       

17:46.668 --> 17:49.135
       Uh, no, I... I...        

17:49.137 --> 17:52.138
       <i>I'm kidding. Ha, ha.</i>     

17:52.140 --> 17:53.772
       <i>I'm a robot. Ha, ha.</i>     

17:53.774 --> 17:56.007
          <i>I'll destroy you</i>      
          <i>with one blow.</i>        

17:56.009 --> 17:58.075
     <i>Ha. Am I right, people?</i>    

17:59.177 --> 18:00.677
        (H.A.M PLAYING          
        STUDIO LAUGHTER)        

18:04.781 --> 18:07.449
        That comedy robot       
        has a dark side.        

18:07.451 --> 18:09.718
  Like, that is not uncommon.   

18:09.720 --> 18:12.220
      Humor is often inspired   
      by the same darkness      

18:12.222 --> 18:14.789
     from which it endeavors    
     to provide an escape.      

18:15.223 --> 18:16.856
              Huh?              

18:16.858 --> 18:19.892
 Wow, I'm so hungry,            
 my brain ain't workin' right.  

18:19.894 --> 18:21.860
 -(HEAVY FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING) 
 -SCOOBY-DOO: Huh?              

18:21.862 --> 18:23.728
          SHAGGY: Yikes!        
          (WHIMPERING)          

18:23.730 --> 18:25.029
           (GRUNTING)           

18:25.031 --> 18:26.830
         -(TEETH CHATTERING)    
         -(WHIMPERING)          

18:30.067 --> 18:32.034
      CLARK: I guess an alien   
      wouldn't shock you.       

18:32.036 --> 18:34.069
        You've seen all kinds   
        of weird stuff.         

18:34.071 --> 18:35.804
       You researched me?       

18:35.806 --> 18:38.439
  Why? You're here              
  to do a piece on the Baron.   

18:38.441 --> 18:42.742
  I'm not sure he's the most    
  interesting person on board.  

18:42.744 --> 18:44.175
       (CLICKING TONGUE)        
       Know what I mean?        

18:47.078 --> 18:48.445
              Ew!               

18:48.447 --> 18:49.879
       -(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING) 
       -(WHIMPERING)            

18:53.717 --> 18:56.919
          Phew! Like, it's you, 
          Mr. U-Boat.           

18:56.921 --> 18:58.620
        We're huge fans.        

18:58.622 --> 19:00.755
   You're like the best player  
   on the field every Sunday    

19:00.757 --> 19:03.924
      and Monday and Thursday   
      and some Saturdays.       

19:03.926 --> 19:06.259
       You're the best          
       off the field too.       

19:06.261 --> 19:07.994
     We love U-Boat Bites.      

19:07.996 --> 19:11.163
 Like, man,                     
 we'd be eating them right now, 

19:11.165 --> 19:13.298
   if the snack bar was open.   

19:16.835 --> 19:18.168
            (GRUNTS)            

19:27.444 --> 19:29.411
      Space is delicious.       

19:34.783 --> 19:36.250
           (GROWLING)           

19:39.954 --> 19:42.088
       DAPHNE: Whoa.            
       Did you hear that?       

19:42.090 --> 19:44.924
   Thermal contraction caused   
   by temperature differential. 
   It's normal.                 

19:44.926 --> 19:46.992
   Right. It's normal, Daph.    

19:47.960 --> 19:49.427
    It didn't sound normal.     

19:49.429 --> 19:52.263
   It sounded like              
   there's something outside.   

19:52.265 --> 19:56.000
         Something outside?     
         You mean in the vacuum 
         of space?              

19:56.002 --> 19:58.635
   -Like what?                  
   -(SCOFFS) Yeah, like what?   

19:58.637 --> 20:00.970
    In the vacuum of space?     

20:00.972 --> 20:02.771
  You think                     
  there's an alien out there?   

20:02.773 --> 20:06.508
   A creature with an oversized 
   head and big black eyes?     

20:06.510 --> 20:08.710
        Hold the phone.         
        You've seen it?         

20:08.712 --> 20:10.611
 No, because it doesn't exist!  

20:10.613 --> 20:13.947
  If aliens exist, they never   
  introduce themselves to us.   

20:13.949 --> 20:16.149
  And we've spent a lot of time 
  in their neighborhood.        

20:16.151 --> 20:17.817
      Not that it matters.      

20:17.819 --> 20:21.020
   Space is dangerous enough    
   without little green men.    

20:21.022 --> 20:23.822
       Maybe they were cloaked  
       from human sight.        

20:23.824 --> 20:26.157
   I saw a movie                
   where the aliens did that.   

20:26.159 --> 20:28.826
   -Here, I'll show you a clip. 
   -No, no, no.                 

20:28.828 --> 20:32.129
 You kids watch so much junk on 
 screens, you think it's real.  

20:32.131 --> 20:35.398
        When I was your age,    
        we watched less         
        and lived more.         

20:35.400 --> 20:38.633
   Makes sense. There was       
   a lot of less stuff to watch 
   when you were our age.       

20:39.201 --> 20:41.001
           (CLANGING)           

20:41.003 --> 20:44.337
     -I mean... Well, of course 
     there was... Oh.           
     -(BEEP)                    

20:44.339 --> 20:45.971
          (INAUDIBLE)           

20:45.973 --> 20:48.139
  Colt, let's get out of here.  

20:51.509 --> 20:53.209
             (BEEP)             

20:53.211 --> 20:55.910
  Uh, maybe you should just     
  give them some space, Fred.   

20:57.712 --> 21:02.581
      (LAUGHING) Get it? Space! 
      That's so funny.          

21:02.583 --> 21:04.149
      I... I don't get it.      

21:04.151 --> 21:05.750
        (ALARM BLARING)         

21:08.086 --> 21:10.187
     -COLT: What did you touch, 
     hotshot?                   
     -Nothing.                  

21:10.189 --> 21:13.356
  ZIP: Come on. Let's go see    
  what all this fuss is about.  

21:13.358 --> 21:15.925
    He called me a hotshot.     

21:15.927 --> 21:18.193
      SLY:  <i>Nothing</i>             
      <i>to worry about, folks,</i>    

21:18.195 --> 21:21.996
    just working out            
    some first flight bugs.     

21:21.998 --> 21:25.566
        Be sure to capture      
        my perfect physique     
         and spirit, hmm?       

21:28.736 --> 21:31.037
 I've said it a thousand times, 

21:31.039 --> 21:33.539
        civilians do not belong 
        in space.               

21:33.541 --> 21:38.042
      You're right, Colt.       
      You've said it a thousand 
      times, at least.          

21:38.044 --> 21:40.711
         Man! (HOWLING)         
         We're doomed.          

21:40.713 --> 21:43.312
      SCOOBY-DOO: How do we     
      get off this thing?       

21:45.948 --> 21:48.215
     -ZIP: What's going on?     
     -It's the air supply.      

21:48.217 --> 21:49.583
     We're venting oxygen.      

21:49.585 --> 21:52.018
    Something must have damaged 
    the external tank.          

21:52.020 --> 21:54.320
     (SNAPS FINGERS)            
     Like the alien we saw.     

21:56.756 --> 21:59.891
       We saw an alien outside, 
       or we didn't.            

21:59.893 --> 22:01.592
   I like "we didn't" better.   

22:01.594 --> 22:04.728
 Did it have black, hollow eyes 
 and slimy looking skin?        

22:04.730 --> 22:06.596
 Like, yeah. (LAUGHS NERVOUSLY) 

22:06.598 --> 22:07.830
       How did you know?        

22:11.100 --> 22:12.300
            Jinkies.            

22:13.702 --> 22:14.802
           (RATTLING)           

22:14.804 --> 22:17.070
 Man, that doesn't sound good.  

22:17.072 --> 22:18.538
        (ALARMS BEEPING)        

22:18.540 --> 22:20.439
  It's not good.                
  We're nearly out of oxygen.   

22:24.977 --> 22:27.511
   -How long do we have? Hours? 
   -More like minutes.          

22:28.746 --> 22:31.547
        -Minutes?               
        -(BOTH PANTING)         

22:31.549 --> 22:33.916
   We need to find air, fast!   

22:33.918 --> 22:37.286
          -(GASPING)            
          -There's a lot of air 
          on Earth.             

22:37.288 --> 22:38.987
     And, like, no aliens.      

22:38.989 --> 22:40.888
       We'll never make it back 
       to Earth in time.        

22:40.890 --> 22:45.058
     Never make it? But there's 
     nowhere else to go.        

22:45.060 --> 22:49.028
      That's not entirely true. 
      There is one place.       

22:51.498 --> 22:54.665
   (CLEARS THROAT)              
   Shouldn't you be             
   filming me being dramatic?   

22:55.299 --> 22:56.932
           Oh, right.           

22:56.934 --> 23:01.069
      That's not entirely true. 
      There is one place.       

23:30.465 --> 23:34.601
    SLY:  <i>You don't need air</i>    
     <i>when something</i>             
     <i>takes your breath away.</i>    

24:12.639 --> 24:14.673
    SHANNON: The Baron has been 
    secretly building           

24:14.675 --> 24:17.308
   on the dark side of the moon 
   for over 10 years.           

24:17.310 --> 24:19.543
     It's quite an achievement, 
     don't you think?           

24:19.545 --> 24:23.913
     Furthering his dream       
     of making space travel     
     available for anyone.      

24:23.915 --> 24:26.515
        You're welcome,         
        average people.         

24:26.517 --> 24:29.251
       I guess he really is     
       a man of mystery.        

24:29.253 --> 24:34.656
  You are the first             
  to experience the very finest 
  space has to offer.           

24:43.064 --> 24:44.631
           (GIGGLING)           

24:53.206 --> 24:55.840
   Welcome to Sly Moon Prime,   

24:55.842 --> 24:58.909
         the moon's first       
         luxury resort.         

24:58.911 --> 25:03.079
   It's not quite finished yet, 
   but the air generators       
   are on line                  

25:03.081 --> 25:06.282
  and producing more air        
  than we could ever breathe.   

25:06.284 --> 25:07.349
       (BREATHES DEEPLY)        

25:13.789 --> 25:16.357
             -Your helmet?      
             -What?             

25:16.359 --> 25:17.891
         Oh, forget it.         

25:17.893 --> 25:21.628
     Anything you want or need, 
     just ask a Sly Bot.        

25:21.630 --> 25:24.530
      -That's why we made them. 
      -MAN: We?                 

25:28.567 --> 25:30.234
           Forgive me.          
           (CHUCKLES)           

25:30.236 --> 25:34.104
  I had little to do            
  with actually building them.  

25:34.106 --> 25:38.574
 Nothing but the money          
 to make all of this possible.  

25:38.576 --> 25:41.810
    This is Hudson,             
    my right hand space man     

25:41.812 --> 25:44.279
      and my twin brother.      

25:45.247 --> 25:46.313
         He made them.          

25:46.315 --> 25:48.982
        (H.A.M. PLAYING         
        DRAMATIC MUSIC)         

25:55.289 --> 25:56.656
              <i>Sorry.</i>            

25:56.658 --> 25:59.792
 He's been here since day one.  

25:59.794 --> 26:03.262
   11 years, two months,        
   12 days, most of it alone.   

26:03.264 --> 26:05.264
     It's great                 
     to see friendly faces.     

26:05.266 --> 26:07.766
         Or any faces at all.   
         (FORCED LAUGH)         

26:07.768 --> 26:08.833
          (WHIMPERING)          

26:10.335 --> 26:11.902
              Mmm?              

26:14.105 --> 26:17.273
     This isn't all happening   
     in my head, is it?         
     It's all real, right?      

26:17.275 --> 26:19.141
      Yes, it is, brother.      

26:20.776 --> 26:23.945
        People, people, people! 
        (LAUGHING)              

26:23.947 --> 26:27.581
        People, people, people. 
        You're really here.     
        You're all real.        

26:27.583 --> 26:29.082
       (LAUGHING)               
       It's been so long.       

26:29.084 --> 26:31.684
     I love him,                
     but he's a little odd.     

26:31.686 --> 26:34.620
     Hudson, why don't you      
     make the introduction?     

26:34.622 --> 26:37.889
 Yes, yes, yes. Introductions.  

26:37.891 --> 26:41.225
    This is Frank.              
    He keeps us all honest.     

26:41.227 --> 26:42.793
         This is Linda,         

26:44.128 --> 26:45.461
      our ray of sunshine.      

26:47.764 --> 26:50.799
   Here's Reggie,               
   the comedian of the group.   

26:52.234 --> 26:54.435
           (LAUGHING)           

26:54.437 --> 26:57.504
      Good one, Reggie.         
      (CONTINUES LAUGHING)      

26:58.606 --> 27:00.406
    Oh... Oh, that's funny.     

27:00.408 --> 27:01.640
        (CLEARS THROAT)         

27:03.609 --> 27:05.776
  And finally, there's Twiggy.  

27:05.778 --> 27:07.911
        She's not happy with me 
        at the moment.          

27:07.913 --> 27:11.613
   We're having a disagreement, 
   isn't that right?            

27:14.049 --> 27:15.582
        Oh, is that so?         

27:15.584 --> 27:18.251
       Well, we'll talk         
       about this later.        

27:18.253 --> 27:21.254
  So, what can we do for you?   

27:21.256 --> 27:24.090
      We need to patch and seal 
      our air tanks.            

27:24.092 --> 27:25.758
       Gonna need               
       two welding rigs.        

27:25.760 --> 27:28.293
       -Make it three.          
       -Like I said, two.       

27:28.295 --> 27:31.162
  Yes, yes, of course!          
  I'll put my best bot on it.   

27:31.164 --> 27:33.797
     (GASPING)                  
     That's Caroline Prime!     

27:35.099 --> 27:36.466
           (BEEPING)            

27:45.642 --> 27:47.175
            (GULPS)             

27:47.177 --> 27:49.143
   Caroline, we have guests!    

27:49.145 --> 27:51.512
       (WHEELS SQUEAKING)       

28:03.124 --> 28:05.925
          Stop. Stay.           

28:05.927 --> 28:08.127
       She was just             
       stocking supplies.       

28:08.129 --> 28:11.163
     She can move thousands     
     of food crates in a matter 
     of minutes. (CHUCKLES)     

28:11.165 --> 28:13.031
     Food crates! (LAUGHS)      

28:13.033 --> 28:15.633
   Like, I think I found        
   my favorite robot, Scoob.    

28:15.635 --> 28:17.768
         Yeah, me too.          

28:19.537 --> 28:21.404
              (H.A.M PLAYING    
              STUDIO RECORDING) 
               <i>Aw!</i>              

28:25.142 --> 28:27.943
       I don't trust anything   
       that's not human.        

28:27.945 --> 28:30.312
       Maybe you shouldn't get  
       too close, U-Boat.       

28:30.314 --> 28:33.315
      She's perfectly safe.     
      Wouldn't hurt a fly.      

28:33.317 --> 28:36.384
 I checked her protocol myself. 
 She'll do anything we ask.     

28:36.386 --> 28:37.618
          Watch. Sit!           

28:39.687 --> 28:42.989
       Oh. (GIGGLING)           
       Not you. Caroline.       

28:42.991 --> 28:44.557
         Caroline, sit.         

28:45.959 --> 28:47.726
    It'll take some time        
    to get the rigs prepped.    

28:47.728 --> 28:49.461
       And of course,           
       you'll be needing        

28:49.463 --> 28:53.231
  cryogen down the mag coils    
  and synthenix first, right?   

28:56.468 --> 28:59.102
       He said the engines      
       will need to cool.       

29:00.337 --> 29:01.870
         That's right.          

29:06.174 --> 29:07.607
              Oh!               

29:14.548 --> 29:16.414
     (VELMA CLEARS THROAT)      

29:18.517 --> 29:21.018
      -I speak nerd.            
      -Of course, you do.       

29:21.020 --> 29:23.854
     -Watch it, four eyes!      
     -You wear glasses too.     

29:23.856 --> 29:25.755
       (SCOFFS) Whatever.       

29:25.757 --> 29:28.190
       Okay, good, good.        
       Let's get to work.       

29:28.192 --> 29:29.858
       -Might take a day or so. 
       -DAPHNE: Great.          

29:29.860 --> 29:32.026
  That will give us             
  a chance to find the alien.   

29:32.028 --> 29:33.727
        -Alien?                 
        -(H.A.M. PLAYING        
        DRAMATIC MUSIC)         

29:35.029 --> 29:37.330
    Uh, you're not helping.     

29:37.931 --> 29:39.765
              <i>Sorry.</i>            

29:39.767 --> 29:42.367
  That's what ripped the oxygen 
  lines on the  <i>Sly Star One.</i>   

29:42.369 --> 29:44.168
  It could still be on board.   

29:44.170 --> 29:46.603
   Or around here somewhere.    

29:47.871 --> 29:49.504
    Who knows what you saw?     

29:49.506 --> 29:51.439
        It was probably nothing 
        but space junk.         

29:51.441 --> 29:53.541
       Come on, Zip,            
       let's get to work.       

29:53.543 --> 29:55.576
   Right, let's get to work.    

29:55.578 --> 30:00.414
   I'm afraid                   
   I have to excuse myself      
   for a satellite interview,   

30:00.416 --> 30:05.018
    probably about              
    some award the world        
    needs to bestow upon me.    

30:05.020 --> 30:09.054
    Um, feel free to take       
    the Sly Moon buggy ride.    

30:09.056 --> 30:10.622
      It's fun out there.       

30:10.624 --> 30:13.725
      Now, watch me leave!      

30:13.727 --> 30:16.394
 Like, dude,                    
 if the alien might be inside,  

30:16.396 --> 30:18.195
        maybe we should go      
        where it isn't.         

30:18.197 --> 30:19.930
         Like, outside.         

30:19.932 --> 30:21.364
   What do you say, old pal?    

30:21.366 --> 30:23.232
      Yeah, yeah, outside.      

30:23.234 --> 30:25.367
  I'm right behind you, buddy.  

30:25.369 --> 30:27.035
   So, where should we start?   

30:27.037 --> 30:29.237
        I have to recalibrate   
        the oxygen levels       
        for the station.        

30:29.239 --> 30:32.106
    More people,                
    more air to breathe.        
    Shouldn't take too long.    

30:32.108 --> 30:33.373
     I'll see you in a bit.     

30:35.642 --> 30:37.909
           (GIGGLING)           

30:37.911 --> 30:42.579
  So, Clark, didn't you mention 
  that you wanted to do         
  an exclusive expose           

30:42.581 --> 30:45.448
  on someone                    
  in the mystery solving game?  

30:45.450 --> 30:48.050
     That someone being me!     

30:48.551 --> 30:50.618
             Hmph!              

30:50.620 --> 30:53.187
             Oh, yeah. Well...  
             Whoa!              

30:58.258 --> 30:59.558
          <i>Knock, knock.</i>         

30:59.560 --> 31:02.694
      I'm not home,             
      but these guys are.       

31:06.098 --> 31:07.998
              (H.A.M. PLAYING   
              STUDIO RECORDING) 
               <i>Aw!</i>              

31:12.436 --> 31:14.003
        Yeah! Whoo-hoo!         

31:14.005 --> 31:16.939
    Yeah! Scooby-Dooby-Doo!     

31:16.941 --> 31:18.340
           (GIGGLING)           

31:34.322 --> 31:36.356
       That Colt guy            
       was right, Scoob.        

31:36.358 --> 31:38.291
      Maybe it wasn't           
      an alien after all.       

31:38.293 --> 31:40.593
          Maybe it was just     
          space junk.           

31:40.595 --> 31:43.963
    I mean, look at this place. 
    It's a regular junkyard.    

31:43.965 --> 31:47.633
 (ECHOING)                      
 Junkyard. Junkyard. Junkyard.  

31:47.635 --> 31:51.236
    Yeah. Yeah. Space junkyard. 
    (GIGGLING)                  

31:55.340 --> 31:56.740
           (EXCLAIMS)           

31:57.942 --> 32:00.076
   (CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING)    

32:33.243 --> 32:36.912
  One small step for a dog...   

32:39.348 --> 32:43.918
   And one giant leap for me!   

32:43.920 --> 32:46.320
        -Yeah.                  
        -(BOTH LAUGHING)        

32:46.322 --> 32:49.588
   That's weird.                
   I thought we left            
   the dark side of the moon.   

32:52.224 --> 32:53.958
           (GROWLING)           

32:55.160 --> 32:56.460
           (BEEPING)            

32:57.361 --> 32:58.561
          (SCREAMING)           

33:30.292 --> 33:31.358
           (GROWLING)           

33:38.399 --> 33:39.465
            Zoinks!             

33:39.467 --> 33:41.233
          -Catch me!            
          -Okay, dude!          

33:41.235 --> 33:43.001
       -Scoob!                  
       -(ENGINE STARTING)       

33:48.707 --> 33:49.773
            Shaggy!             

33:49.775 --> 33:52.142
       (SHAGGY SHOUTING)        

33:52.144 --> 33:53.843
       (BOTH WHIMPERING)        

34:02.252 --> 34:03.485
          (SCREAMING)           

34:12.460 --> 34:13.525
           (HISSING)            

34:25.737 --> 34:26.771
         (SHAGGY GASPS)         

34:26.773 --> 34:27.905
              Hmm.              

34:29.274 --> 34:31.608
   I think we lost it, Scoob.   

34:31.610 --> 34:32.842
             (BEEP)             

34:33.810 --> 34:34.976
           (EXCLAIMS)           

34:35.944 --> 34:37.643
       (BOTH WHIMPERING)        

34:39.780 --> 34:42.248
     Like, we're totally sorry, 
     Mr. U-Boat,                

34:42.250 --> 34:44.248
 but that alien was chasing us. 

34:46.918 --> 34:48.953
   Really?                      
   You must have been scared.   

34:48.955 --> 34:51.621
      Scared? (STAMMERING)      

34:51.623 --> 34:53.389
          Like, why would you   
          think that?           

34:57.294 --> 35:00.195
 That's okay, I get scared too. 

35:00.197 --> 35:02.263
     Like, you get scared?      

35:02.265 --> 35:04.131
       (GASPING) Of what?       

35:04.133 --> 35:06.033
            Of what?            

35:06.035 --> 35:09.069
        Sharks, dentists,       
        public speaking,        

35:09.071 --> 35:12.738
        aliens, mines, the IRS, 
        being in space,         

35:12.740 --> 35:14.339
        lots of things!         

35:16.075 --> 35:18.242
     Sometimes it's all         
     in your head, though.      

35:18.244 --> 35:20.811
 The trick is finding something 
 that helps you deal with it.   

35:20.813 --> 35:22.312
           -Like food.          
           -Or music.           

35:22.314 --> 35:24.314
         -BOTH: Or food.        
         -Or exercise.          

35:24.316 --> 35:25.481
         BOTH: Or food.         

35:25.483 --> 35:27.249
         -Hey, or maybe even... 
         -Food!                 

35:27.251 --> 35:29.117
        -...Singing.            
        -BOTH: Or food.         

35:32.654 --> 35:34.388
     Singing... (LAUGHING)      

35:34.390 --> 35:37.791
        -Like, you sing?        
        That's funny.           
        -(BOTH LAUGHING)        

35:40.494 --> 35:41.660
      (SOFT MUSIC STARTS)       

35:43.262 --> 35:48.298
        <i>¶ Fear is just a word</i>   
        <i>a four letter word</i>      

35:48.300 --> 35:54.570
           <i>¶ Like love and meek</i> 
           <i>and made</i>             

35:54.572 --> 35:59.474
       <i>¶ Only just a word</i>       
       <i>a silly little word</i>      

35:59.476 --> 36:04.244
         <i>¶ So it doesn't</i>        
         <i>make me afraid ¶</i>       

36:06.513 --> 36:07.779
        Wow! That is...         

36:07.781 --> 36:09.180
         <i>¶ F la la la la</i>        

36:09.182 --> 36:10.648
         <i>¶ E la la la la</i>        

36:10.650 --> 36:12.916
        <i>¶ A la la la la R</i>       

36:12.918 --> 36:18.020
         <i>¶ Spells nothing</i>       
         <i>you need to fear</i>       

36:18.955 --> 36:21.489
      <i>¶ Fear is just a word</i>     

36:21.491 --> 36:23.991
      <i>¶ A silly little word</i>     

36:23.993 --> 36:29.830
         <i>¶ So it doesn't</i>        
         <i>make me afraid ¶</i>       

36:34.501 --> 36:35.667
              Huh.              

36:38.303 --> 36:39.770
         (DOOR OPENING)         

36:50.180 --> 36:52.781
  Wow!                          
  Look at all this cool stuff.  

36:52.783 --> 36:55.150
     I don't even know          
     what half of it does.      

36:55.152 --> 36:56.351
       (TOOLS CLATTERING)       

36:56.353 --> 36:58.986
        Check this out.         

36:58.988 --> 37:00.387
          Maybe you shouldn't   
          touch that.           

37:00.389 --> 37:02.021
           (WHIRRING)           

37:02.023 --> 37:04.189
   It's a coolant gel used      
   to extinguish fires by...    

37:04.191 --> 37:05.490
              Ah!               

37:05.492 --> 37:07.325
        ...totally immersing it 
        in gel.                 

37:07.327 --> 37:10.161
    -Fred!                      
    -Sorry, Daph. Let me...     

37:10.163 --> 37:12.129
         (GASPING) Wow!         

37:12.131 --> 37:13.630
      Look at this thing.       

37:13.632 --> 37:15.465
  I wouldn't touch that, Fred.  

37:15.467 --> 37:17.233
   It's oxygen                  
   and butyl liquid nitrogen.   

37:17.235 --> 37:18.567
      If that goes off...       

37:23.873 --> 37:25.573
    Zip, what are you doing?    

37:25.575 --> 37:27.808
          -I'm going to get him 
          out of there.         
          -Really?              

37:27.810 --> 37:30.076
  You think that's a good idea? 
  You hear that?                

37:34.914 --> 37:37.282
  It's really quiet, peaceful,  

37:40.552 --> 37:44.254
    -no Fred talking.           
    -Oh, right. (CHUCKLING)     

37:48.692 --> 37:50.826
        How long can someone    
        survive in that?        

37:50.828 --> 37:53.028
       Well, it depends.        

37:53.030 --> 37:56.130
   How long you want to enjoy   
   the blissful sound           
   of not hearing his voice?    

37:56.998 --> 37:59.232
         Uh, half hour?         

37:59.234 --> 38:01.100
   Yeah, sounds about right.    

38:01.102 --> 38:02.734
  Now, hand me those calipers.  

38:02.736 --> 38:04.469
       (DAPHNE STRAINING)       

38:07.939 --> 38:09.272
           (BEEPING)            

38:15.578 --> 38:17.278
           (SIZZLING)           

38:19.080 --> 38:20.580
           <i>Interesting.</i>         

38:22.883 --> 38:25.851
    <i>I thought you didn't trust</i>  
    <i>anything that's not human.</i>  

38:25.853 --> 38:29.354
 <i>A microwave isn't human,</i>       
 <i>yet you let it make your food.</i> 

38:39.698 --> 38:41.965
        <i>You'll be needing this,</i> 
        <i>I suppose?</i>              

38:41.967 --> 38:44.333
               <i>Another machine.</i> 
               <i>See?</i>             

38:45.735 --> 38:48.069
       <i>Machines are useful.</i>     

38:48.071 --> 38:49.937
           <i>-Machines are...</i>     
          <i> -(GROWLING)</i>          

38:56.577 --> 38:58.144
          (H.A.M. PLAYING       
          SOUNDTRACK RECORDING) 
           <i>Ooh...</i>               

39:01.314 --> 39:04.648
   Jinkies! You really          
   don't like robots, do you?   

39:07.118 --> 39:09.486
     I guess you don't take     
     to progress very well.     

39:09.488 --> 39:11.921
           Progress?            

39:11.923 --> 39:15.224
  You mean the sort of progress 
  that put automated machines   
  in the car factories?         

39:15.226 --> 39:18.760
  The sort of progress that put 
  my father and hundreds        
  of others like him            

39:18.762 --> 39:20.728
 out of work when I was a kid?  

39:20.730 --> 39:22.663
     That sort of progress?     

39:29.169 --> 39:32.337
    Boy, if he had his way,     
    we wouldn't have planes,    

39:32.339 --> 39:34.905
      let alone the technology  
      to fly to the moon.       

39:35.640 --> 39:36.873
              Hmm.              

39:41.110 --> 39:42.677
 SHAGGY: Maybe U-Boat's right.  

39:42.679 --> 39:45.045
      Maybe that alien was only 
      in our heads.             

39:46.914 --> 39:48.014
              Hmm?              

39:48.949 --> 39:51.984
  Yeah, just like that alien.   

39:51.986 --> 39:54.019
           (GROWLING)           

39:54.021 --> 39:56.854
       Yep, that alien's        
       not really there.        

39:58.523 --> 40:01.691
     -(GROWLING)                
     -Neither is that one.      

40:01.693 --> 40:04.293
       -Or that one!            
       -(BOTH SCREAMING)        

40:04.295 --> 40:06.228
             Yikes!             

40:14.136 --> 40:15.603
       Have we lost him?        

40:15.605 --> 40:18.939
    -I think we're okay, Scoob. 
    -Yeah, more than okay.      

40:30.484 --> 40:31.650
      (EXCLAIMS JOYFULLY)       

40:31.652 --> 40:33.451
     There's no alien. Yup!     

40:33.453 --> 40:37.854
 No alien at all.               
 We're just hungry, that's all. 

40:37.856 --> 40:41.224
        Yeah, we need to eat    
        that alien away.        

40:41.226 --> 40:43.526
        (BOTH LAUGHING)         

40:47.630 --> 40:49.831
     I feel better already.     

40:49.833 --> 40:50.998
         Me too, Scoob.         

40:51.000 --> 40:53.867
   This spread is, uh... Huh?   

40:53.869 --> 40:55.068
           (GROWLING)           

40:55.070 --> 40:56.769
       (BOTH WHIMPERING)        

41:11.317 --> 41:12.917
        I am so scared!         

41:13.351 --> 41:15.251
            Me, too!            

41:15.986 --> 41:17.252
            (SNARLS)            

41:32.700 --> 41:36.536
   Sorry, Mr. Alien.            
   Like this table's for two.   

41:36.538 --> 41:40.673
       Plus, he can't reach it, 
       unless aliens can        
       jump really high.        

41:40.675 --> 41:43.275
  Can aliens jump really high?  

41:43.277 --> 41:44.843
          (GROWLING))           

41:55.521 --> 41:56.954
          (SCREAMING)           

42:03.728 --> 42:05.794
       (BOTH WHIMPERING)        

42:07.263 --> 42:09.264
           (GROWLING)           

42:09.266 --> 42:10.665
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

42:26.547 --> 42:29.582
 (PANTING) So, you              
 guys were on                   
 the very first mission, right? 

42:29.584 --> 42:31.216
        That's so cool.         

42:31.218 --> 42:33.084
   You probably have a huge     
   following on the Internet.   

42:33.086 --> 42:35.286
           Have your own blog?  
           But it wasn't around 
           back then.           

42:35.288 --> 42:38.154
 Heck, I don't think there were 
 even computers back then.      
 (LAUGHING)                     

42:40.257 --> 42:42.992
      Aw! We should have        
      left him in the ice.      

42:42.994 --> 42:45.094
 I still can't feel my fingers. 

42:45.096 --> 42:47.996
        Ew! What's that?        

42:47.998 --> 42:50.765
      Condensation. Probably    
      from the air vents.       

42:50.767 --> 42:52.933
 Looks like alien juice to me.  

42:52.935 --> 42:55.369
      And you've seen           
      alien juice before?       

42:55.371 --> 42:57.104
        No, not exactly.        

42:57.106 --> 42:59.206
  But if I were to take a guess 
  at what it looked like,       

42:59.208 --> 43:01.841
     I would say it would       
     look a lot like that.      

43:01.843 --> 43:03.576
 Could this day get any worse?  

43:03.578 --> 43:05.945
          -(BOTH SCREAMING)     
          -(CRASHING)           

43:07.213 --> 43:08.913
  What the blazes is going on?  

43:08.915 --> 43:10.381
          Alien! Big!           

43:10.383 --> 43:12.683
    (WHIMPERING) Chasing us!    

43:12.685 --> 43:16.153
   Yeah! It hates food          
   and likes melting brains.    

43:20.124 --> 43:24.227
  -Maybe it's lost.             
  -Or maybe it doesn't exist!   

43:24.229 --> 43:26.262
       Wait, where did          
       you see an alien?        

43:26.264 --> 43:27.963
       Dude, restaurant!        

43:27.965 --> 43:30.065
     And you left before        
     you were done eating?      

43:30.067 --> 43:31.733
         BOTH: Uh-huh.          

43:31.735 --> 43:35.136
 Shaggy and Scooby              
 would never leave food behind. 

43:35.138 --> 43:36.704
      Something was             
      in that restaurant.       

43:36.706 --> 43:38.138
     And that's the truth!      

43:38.140 --> 43:40.573
          -So help me hot dogs. 
          -Okay!                

43:40.575 --> 43:42.074
     Let's go take a look.      

43:42.076 --> 43:44.810
   Oh, sure. Why not?           
   I could use a good laugh.    

43:44.812 --> 43:47.612
        (H.A.M PLAYING          
        STUDIO LAUGHTER)        

43:49.147 --> 43:51.414
       That's not funny.        

43:51.416 --> 43:54.283
   Look at this.                
   It's lucky no one's hurt.    

43:54.285 --> 43:56.485
     Tell that to               
     the poor spring rolls.     

43:56.487 --> 43:59.221
     Or to anybody replaced     
     by an alien imposter.      

43:59.223 --> 44:01.256
     Because they do that.      

44:01.258 --> 44:02.790
 Better the food than the ship. 

44:02.792 --> 44:05.726
  -Watch your mouth, Hollywood. 
  -(GROWLING)                   

44:05.728 --> 44:09.262
     Shaggy is very sensitive   
     when it comes to food.     

44:09.264 --> 44:11.230
        Well, it could          
        have been worse.        

44:11.232 --> 44:13.765
  Exactly. Good point, Daphne.  

44:13.767 --> 44:15.933
    Yes, Daphne, well done.     

44:15.935 --> 44:18.634
 It's lucky we have             
 a space expert like you here.  

44:20.136 --> 44:21.402
       What's that about?       

44:22.003 --> 44:23.636
        I have an idea.         

44:25.271 --> 44:26.904
  Talked to the chef Sly bot.   

44:26.906 --> 44:29.306
   He didn't say anything,      
   maybe because he's scared.   

44:29.308 --> 44:31.841
      Or maybe because          
      Sly bots can't talk.      

44:31.843 --> 44:33.776
           Uh, right.           

44:33.778 --> 44:35.644
   So we have two witnesses.    

44:35.646 --> 44:38.346
    Right, who are eating       
    raw fish off the floor.     

44:40.015 --> 44:41.915
        Come on, Zip.           
        This is a joke!         

44:41.917 --> 44:44.417
   There's no alien             
   and we've got work to do.    

44:44.419 --> 44:46.419
          -(LOUD THUDDING)      
          -(SCREAMING)          

44:49.623 --> 44:51.123
           It's back!           

44:51.125 --> 44:54.359
      SLY: Looks like I missed  
      one heck of a party.      

44:54.361 --> 44:57.328
    Well, look who shows up     

44:57.330 --> 44:59.630
      right after               
      all the excitement.       

44:59.632 --> 45:01.431
    Perfect timing, I'd say.    

45:01.433 --> 45:03.933
     I was about to give        
     a satellite interview,     

45:03.935 --> 45:05.935
      about me, of course.      

45:05.937 --> 45:09.605
   But it appears               
   someone or something         
   put it out of commission.    

45:09.607 --> 45:10.806
     The satellite is out?      

45:10.808 --> 45:12.841
   We're cut off from Earth.    

45:12.843 --> 45:15.543
        No way of communicating 
        to anyone.              

45:17.979 --> 45:20.113
           (GASPING)            

45:20.115 --> 45:22.148
          (WHIMPERING)          

45:22.150 --> 45:25.017
       -It must have            
       happened right before... 
       -The alien attack!       

45:25.019 --> 45:27.986
         Don't worry, folks.    
         I'll be fine.          

45:27.988 --> 45:30.855
     -Besides, Hudson is on it. 
     -Mmm-hmm.                  

45:30.857 --> 45:34.658
 And the Sly bots are preparing 
 more food as we speak.         

45:34.660 --> 45:36.793
      Wow! Awesome boots!       

45:36.795 --> 45:39.128
     Yes, they are awesome,     

45:39.130 --> 45:40.629
     because they're on me.     

45:40.631 --> 45:43.832
    They're my brother's latest 
    magna-boot prototype.       

45:43.834 --> 45:49.070
     It creates a pressure      
     sensitive electromagnetic  
     field for attraction.      

45:49.072 --> 45:51.372
      I think you might know    
      a thing or two about      

45:51.374 --> 45:53.741
  electromagnetic attraction.   

45:53.743 --> 45:55.876
     -Am I right?               
     -You can't be serious.     

45:55.878 --> 45:58.845
    I think I may throw up.     
    Really, are you serious?    

45:58.847 --> 45:59.979
             Sorry.             

45:59.981 --> 46:02.014
         And repulsion.         

46:02.016 --> 46:03.882
 That's more accurate, I'd say. 

46:03.884 --> 46:05.850
      Very handy in space.      

46:05.852 --> 46:08.252
        Handy for creating      
        a spectacle too.        

46:08.254 --> 46:11.188
  No one creates                
  a spectacle quite like you.   

46:11.190 --> 46:13.190
       (LAUGHING)               
       What, a spectacle?       

46:13.192 --> 46:15.525
 Right you are, Velma Dinkley.  

46:15.527 --> 46:19.028
 And an alien attack is the     
 greatest spectacle of all, no? 

46:19.030 --> 46:20.596
       Are you suggesting       

46:20.598 --> 46:24.332
   I had something to do        
   with this alien situation?   

46:24.334 --> 46:25.900
   Well, if the boot fits...    

46:30.037 --> 46:31.504
           (LAUGHING)           

46:36.042 --> 46:38.309
           I get it...          
           (GUFFAWS)            

46:41.046 --> 46:43.514
  I wish I had thought of it.   

46:43.516 --> 46:45.249
   And I probably would have,   

46:45.251 --> 46:49.186
    if I wasn't too busy        
    doing interviews            
    about how awesome I am.     

46:49.188 --> 46:52.856
     An alien encounter is      
     a publicity gold mine.     

46:52.858 --> 46:55.625
       There's only one thing   
       that would top it.       

46:55.627 --> 46:57.226
     An alien space battle.     

46:57.228 --> 46:59.394
 -Well...                       
 -DAPHNE: Or an alien wedding.  

46:59.396 --> 47:01.229
 -No...                         
 -How about an alien cook off?  

47:01.231 --> 47:02.363
              No!               

47:02.365 --> 47:04.932
     An alien in captivity!     

47:11.438 --> 47:14.106
  Too bad for you               
  there's no alien to capture.  

47:14.108 --> 47:16.741
        -You can't say          
        for certain that...     
        -Oh, yes, I can!        

47:16.743 --> 47:20.410
 Last count, I'm pretty sure    
 Colt and I have been to space  
 a whole lot more times than... 

47:20.412 --> 47:22.712
   Gentlemen, ladies, please!   

47:22.714 --> 47:25.414
        It's been a long day.   
        We're all tired.        

47:25.416 --> 47:27.716
       And maybe it's making us 
       a little uneasy.         

47:27.718 --> 47:29.451
        Why don't we all        
        get some sleep?         

47:29.453 --> 47:33.655
 Excellent suggestion, Shannon. 
 I'm glad I thought of it.      

47:34.990 --> 47:37.758
      A few hours' sleep        
      will do us all good.      

47:37.760 --> 47:41.428
  The  <i>Sly Star</i> should be ready 
  by then too. Right, brother?  

47:41.430 --> 47:42.896
          Yes. Uh-huh.          

47:45.966 --> 47:47.199
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

47:50.102 --> 47:52.670
        Like, man, I don't know 
        about you guys,         

47:52.672 --> 47:55.906
     but I won't be getting     
     much sleep with that       
     alien still out there.     

47:55.908 --> 47:57.574
       Yeah, me neither.        

47:58.609 --> 48:00.977
    Guys, there is no alien.    

48:00.979 --> 48:03.179
   But Velma, we all saw it.    

48:03.181 --> 48:05.848
         Oh, I forgot.          

48:05.850 --> 48:08.016
     You're the expert now.     

48:08.018 --> 48:11.119
  Are you still mad             
  at me because I scored        
  higher than you on the test?  

48:11.121 --> 48:12.653
     And have better hair?      

48:20.361 --> 48:23.296
     Guys, I need you to take   
     a break from arguing.      

48:23.298 --> 48:25.331
         We're a team.          

48:25.333 --> 48:27.700
      There's only one way      
      to find out if this alien 
      is real or not.           

48:27.702 --> 48:29.468
     We've got to catch it!     

48:29.470 --> 48:30.702
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

48:32.337 --> 48:34.805
       Did someone say,         
       "Catch an alien"?        

48:34.807 --> 48:37.874
 (H.A.M PLAYING DRAMATIC MUSIC) 

48:40.477 --> 48:42.377
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

48:48.951 --> 48:51.986
 This is going to be            
 the greatest alien trap ever.  

48:51.988 --> 48:54.555
   Isn't this technically       
   the first alien trap ever?   

48:54.557 --> 48:56.523
   It is also an act of war.    

48:56.525 --> 48:58.391
      All the more reason       
      to make it perfect.       

48:58.393 --> 49:01.727
        Plus, I want to impress 
        Zip and Colt.           

49:01.729 --> 49:04.329
  Kind of tough to impress them 
  if they aren't here.          

49:04.331 --> 49:07.231
  Have you considered that      
  they may not warm up to you?  

49:07.233 --> 49:10.467
        -No matter what you do? 
        -No. Why?               

49:10.469 --> 49:12.202
       (SIGHS) No reason.       

49:14.338 --> 49:17.039
     Aliens would laugh         
     at this trap if they       
     had a sense of humor.      

49:19.142 --> 49:21.143
            -But they don't.    
            -(SIGHS)            

49:21.844 --> 49:24.011
         Okay, for fun,         

49:24.013 --> 49:26.013
   let's say aliens are real.   

49:26.015 --> 49:27.581
        What do you think       
        is gonna happen?        

49:27.583 --> 49:30.350
  This is phase one. Contact.   

49:30.352 --> 49:33.820
    RIDLEY:  <i>A single alien</i>     
      <i>from a race advanced</i>      
     <i>light years beyond ours</i>    

49:33.822 --> 49:36.355
     <i>stealthily boards</i>          
     <i>a human ship with ease.</i>    

49:36.357 --> 49:38.156
     <i>The alien makes contact.</i>   

49:38.158 --> 49:41.859
    <i>It seems hostile</i>            
    <i>but it's not after blood.</i>   

49:41.861 --> 49:44.328
  <i>It's gathering intel from us.</i> 

49:44.330 --> 49:48.198
   <i>The alien pinpoints</i>          
   <i>our weaknesses and transmits</i> 
   <i>his findings home.</i>           

49:48.200 --> 49:51.534
 <i>So begins phase two. Invasion.</i> 

49:51.536 --> 49:53.602
        <i>An alien fleet enters</i>   
        <i>our solar system,</i>       

49:53.604 --> 49:55.737
   <i>an armada</i>                    
   <i>of infinite size and power.</i>  

49:55.739 --> 49:58.172
        <i>It surrounds</i>            
        <i>its target, Earth!</i>      

49:58.174 --> 50:00.107
           <i>And attacks.</i>         

50:00.109 --> 50:03.176
     <i>Our meager defenses</i>        
     <i>are no match for its</i>       
     <i>vast and superior might.</i>   

50:03.178 --> 50:05.745
   <i>The world's greatest cities</i>  
   <i>are devastated by the siege.</i> 

50:05.747 --> 50:08.214
         <i>New York, Tokyo,</i>       
         <i>Paris, Dublin...</i>       

50:08.216 --> 50:11.984
    <i>Which leads to phase three.</i> 
    <i>Rock Bottom.</i>                

50:15.888 --> 50:18.289
   <i>The aliens enslave humanity,</i> 

50:18.291 --> 50:23.793
  forcing us to mine Earth's    
  natural resources until we    
  and the planet are bled dry.  

50:24.728 --> 50:27.629
     In short, not so good.     

50:27.631 --> 50:29.297
          Not until...          

50:29.299 --> 50:31.832
   Human rebels rise up against 
   their alien oppressors.      

50:40.241 --> 50:44.810
FRED:  <i>They fight from</i>          
 <i>the shadows turning alien</i>      
 <i>technology against its makers.</i> 

50:46.813 --> 50:48.947
      Wait, what?               
      No, no, no, no, no.       

50:48.949 --> 50:50.715
       As I was saying...       

50:50.717 --> 50:54.384
 Humans stick together when     
 facing a monumental challenge. 

50:56.286 --> 50:59.288
 DAPHNE:  <i>They fight with,</i>      
 <i>instead of against each other,</i> 

50:59.290 --> 51:01.523
         <i>when confronting</i>       
         <i>a common threat.</i>       

51:24.112 --> 51:25.645
           (GIGGLING)           

51:25.647 --> 51:28.615
       I could use my superior  
       video game skills.       

51:36.890 --> 51:38.023
           (PINGING)            

51:59.077 --> 52:01.144
      This is my thing.         
      I get to say what...      

52:01.146 --> 52:04.714
     It takes more than         
     teamwork and video games   
     to defeat the aliens.      

52:10.820 --> 52:13.555
 VELMA:  <i>It takes a particularly</i>
 <i>clever human,</i>                  

52:13.557 --> 52:17.225
      <i>whose skills are</i>          
      <i>sometimes overlooked</i>      
      <i>by her fellow humans.</i>     

52:26.935 --> 52:28.402
             Great.             

52:28.404 --> 52:30.337
 -Nothing left for me to say... 
 -Or maybe...                   

53:15.015 --> 53:17.282
    Oh, this is ridiculous!     

53:17.284 --> 53:19.217
          I'm leaving.          

53:19.219 --> 53:21.152
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

53:21.154 --> 53:22.653
    (ELECTRICITY FLICKERING)    

53:22.655 --> 53:24.821
         It's starting.         
         They're here.          

53:24.823 --> 53:26.556
       Places, everyone!        

53:35.665 --> 53:37.065
        Shaggy, Scooby,         

53:37.067 --> 53:39.901
    I just spotted the alien    
    in the observation deck.    

53:39.903 --> 53:42.637
  Head up there and lure him    
  down to Hudson's work area.   

53:42.639 --> 53:44.839
      Daphne, Velma, and I      
      will cover the rest.      

53:44.841 --> 53:46.507
     It's almost too easy.      

53:46.509 --> 53:47.908
         Any questions?         

53:47.910 --> 53:50.644
     Uh, yeah.                  
     Could we not do this?      

53:50.646 --> 53:52.679
      Guys, relax.              
      It's just an alien.       

53:52.681 --> 53:54.714
     It can't hurt you if       
     it doesn't catch you.      

53:54.716 --> 53:56.182
          Yes, it can.          

53:56.184 --> 53:58.417
  It tried to melt our brains.  

54:06.425 --> 54:08.726
 Man, I don't know about this.  

54:13.531 --> 54:14.597
          (BOTH GASP)           

54:14.599 --> 54:16.332
       BOTH: Sticky buns?       

54:16.334 --> 54:18.400
      FRED:  <i>I figured you might</i>
      <i>have second thoughts.</i>     

54:18.402 --> 54:21.536
     I thought I'd give you two 
     some added incentives.     

54:21.538 --> 54:25.339
      Like, yeah.               
      Incentives with frosting. 
      (CHUCKLING)               

54:25.341 --> 54:27.474
       Yeah. Yeah. Yummy.       

54:32.913 --> 54:36.715
  VELMA: You're probably        
  going to tell me I'm doing    
  this all wrong, aren't you?   

54:36.717 --> 54:41.152
 (SCOFFS) You can't stand       
 that I did better than you on  
 the astronaut training tests.  

54:42.587 --> 54:45.689
  What do I care?               
  Those tests must be flawed.   

54:45.691 --> 54:47.524
  (GASPS) Because I did well?   

54:47.526 --> 54:49.692
      No, because you           
      did better than me.       

54:49.694 --> 54:51.393
        Ugh, I knew it!         

54:51.395 --> 54:54.229
  After all this time, is it so 
  hard for you to accept        

54:54.231 --> 54:56.898
    that I might be something   
    more than a pretty face?    

54:56.900 --> 54:58.032
             No...              

55:02.770 --> 55:04.036
            (SIGHS)             

55:06.806 --> 55:10.241
  What's hard to accept is that 
  you get to have it all.       

55:10.243 --> 55:11.408
      If you're prettier,       

55:11.410 --> 55:13.943
  and more stylish and smarter  

55:13.945 --> 55:16.078
    and a better astronaut,     

55:16.080 --> 55:17.779
      what's left for me?       

55:17.781 --> 55:21.048
         If you're a better me  
         than I am,             
         then who am I?         

55:21.783 --> 55:22.949
              I...              

55:26.486 --> 55:27.986
      -(ELECTRICITY FLICKERING) 
      -(GASPS)                  

55:34.392 --> 55:35.658
              Huh?              

55:38.261 --> 55:39.627
    (ELECTRICITY CRACKLING)     

55:42.430 --> 55:43.496
            Dang it!            

55:43.498 --> 55:45.331
  Tripped the breakers again.   

55:46.299 --> 55:48.066
            (GASPS)             

55:48.068 --> 55:50.268
       Something's wrong        
       with the gravity!        

55:50.270 --> 55:51.836
           You think?           

55:51.838 --> 55:55.673
    What makes you say that?    

55:55.675 --> 55:59.443
  SLY:  <i>Hi, folks. Slight glitch</i>
  <i>with our artificial gravity.</i>  

55:59.445 --> 56:01.144
 <i>We'll have it back on shortly.</i> 

56:01.146 --> 56:03.579
   <i>Until then, enjoy the float.</i> 

56:03.581 --> 56:06.281
 Like, dude, a glitch. Oh, boy! 

56:06.283 --> 56:08.116
    That doesn't sound good.    

56:08.118 --> 56:10.852
   Scoob, what are you doing?   

56:10.854 --> 56:12.820
      Enjoying the float.       

56:12.822 --> 56:14.887
      You can swim              
      without getting wet.      

56:17.357 --> 56:20.292
       (LAUGHING)               
       Hey, you're right.       

56:20.294 --> 56:22.861
    And you can eat             
    without getting sticky.     

56:25.965 --> 56:28.032
         It's all good.         

56:28.034 --> 56:30.367
    Just relax and have a...    

56:30.369 --> 56:31.868
          (GASPS) Huh?          

56:32.636 --> 56:34.602
        (BOTH SCREAMING)        

56:36.471 --> 56:37.971
  Like, what do you say, pal?   

56:37.973 --> 56:40.306
      Maybe we should try some  
      of U-Boat's singing.      

56:40.308 --> 56:41.807
         <i>¶ F la la la la</i>        

56:41.809 --> 56:43.175
         <i>¶ E la la la la</i>        

56:43.177 --> 56:45.477
       <i>¶ A la la la la R </i>       

56:45.479 --> 56:47.912
      -(GROWLS)                 
      -(SINGING CONTINUES)      

56:50.982 --> 56:54.217
    I don't think the singing's 
    working very well, Shag.    

56:54.219 --> 56:56.953
       Guess there's only one   
       thing left to do.        

56:56.955 --> 56:58.220
              Run!              

56:58.222 --> 56:59.888
        (BOTH SCREAMING)        

57:00.522 --> 57:01.922
           (SNARLING)           

57:08.496 --> 57:11.531
       FRED:  <i>Don't eat</i>         
        <i>the sticky buns.</i>        
        <i>Use them to stick.</i>      

57:11.533 --> 57:14.032
    Man. A great idea, Fred.    

57:16.835 --> 57:18.368
         It's working.          

57:19.703 --> 57:21.102
           (GROWLING)           

57:23.538 --> 57:24.971
          (SCREAMING)           

57:33.180 --> 57:35.514
         <i>Rogue One, this</i>        
         <i>is Rogue Leader.</i>       

57:35.516 --> 57:37.849
     <i>The package is</i>             
     <i>heading your way. Over.</i>    

57:37.851 --> 57:40.751
  -Am I Rogue One or Rogue Two? 
  -It doesn't matter.           

57:40.753 --> 57:42.252
       We're ready, Fred.       

57:42.254 --> 57:44.854
   <i>Oh, come on.</i>                 
   <i>Use your call sign, Velma...</i> 

57:44.856 --> 57:48.157
      I mean... (CLEARS THROAT) 
      Rogue Two. Over.          

57:48.159 --> 57:49.791
        (BOTH SCREAMING)        

58:02.270 --> 58:03.637
       Sting darts away!        

58:10.043 --> 58:11.376
        Oh, they missed.        

58:11.378 --> 58:13.444
    <i>No problem. My turn. Over.</i>  

58:16.414 --> 58:18.014
        Like, now what?         

58:18.882 --> 58:20.916
           (GROWLING)           

58:23.052 --> 58:26.420
     Gotcha! Gravity gel.       
     That should hold him.      

58:27.355 --> 58:28.788
       (BOTH EXCLAIMING)        

58:28.790 --> 58:30.623
           (EXCLAIMS)           

58:30.625 --> 58:35.059
      Oh, dude, I guess         
      the gravity's fixed.      

58:35.061 --> 58:37.127
   But now my head's broken.    

58:38.129 --> 58:39.562
           (GROWLING)           

58:39.564 --> 58:40.796
            (GASPS)             

58:53.242 --> 58:54.442
         You caught it!         

58:54.444 --> 58:55.743
     (ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)      

58:55.745 --> 58:57.911
     -The alien!                
     -You caught the alien!     

58:57.913 --> 58:59.145
     -Yes...                    
     -(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)     

58:59.147 --> 59:01.113
     The alien!                 
     You caught the alien!      

59:01.115 --> 59:02.414
     -Yes, we...                
     -(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)     

59:02.416 --> 59:04.282
     The alien!                 
     You caught the alien!      

59:04.284 --> 59:05.616
     -Yes...                    
     -(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)     

59:05.618 --> 59:07.618
      <i>The alien!</i>                
      <i>You caught the alien!</i>     

59:07.620 --> 59:09.052
     -Yes...                    
     -(ELEVATOR BELL DINGS)     

59:09.054 --> 59:11.120
    Does anyone have a spare    
    hair dryer? I seem to...    

59:11.122 --> 59:12.254
           The alien!           

59:12.256 --> 59:14.089
     You caught the alien!      

59:14.091 --> 59:16.224
       Yes, we caught it!       

59:16.226 --> 59:18.992
          -How many elevators   
          are in this building? 
          -It is real.          

59:19.960 --> 59:21.894
     I wouldn't be so sure.     

59:25.398 --> 59:26.831
          (STRAINING)           

59:31.269 --> 59:33.069
      ALL: Shannon Lucas!       

59:35.072 --> 59:37.006
             -But how?          
             -Why?              

59:37.008 --> 59:38.173
              Who?              

59:39.308 --> 59:41.342
    Oh, right. It's Shannon.    

59:41.344 --> 59:42.976
 That's right. It was Shannon.  

59:42.978 --> 59:45.778
    Being an astronaut made her 
    the perfect alien.          

59:45.780 --> 59:49.582
  FRED:  <i>She knew how to adjust</i> 
   <i>the frequency of</i>             
   <i>a micro radar transmitter</i>    

59:49.584 --> 59:53.052
  <i>to turn it into a devastating</i> 
  <i>sonic weapon.</i>                 

59:53.054 --> 59:56.455
    Like, that explains         
    the alien's mind beams.     

59:56.457 --> 59:59.891
  She used Sly's                
  magna-boots to defy gravity.  

59:59.893 --> 01:00:03.227
  VELMA:  <i>And she knew</i>          
   <i>how to use holograms,</i>        
   <i>videos and audio recordings</i>  

01:00:03.229 --> 01:00:05.696
        <i>to mask her whereabouts</i> 
        <i>at any moment.</i>          

01:00:05.698 --> 01:00:09.132
   FRED:  <i>And she knew the ship</i> 
    <i>and the resort, so she</i>      
    <i>could come and go at will.</i>  

01:00:12.569 --> 01:00:16.537
  It was a plan                 
  years in the making           
  by a highly trained expert.   

01:00:16.539 --> 01:00:18.906
        Yes, an expert.         

01:00:18.908 --> 01:00:22.409
    Someone who has sacrificed  
    everything to get here.     

01:00:22.411 --> 01:00:25.578
    Not some regular nobody     
    that Sly had decided        
    could simply go to space    

01:00:25.580 --> 01:00:28.614
 because it was easy            
 and safe for everyone, anyone. 

01:00:28.616 --> 01:00:30.916
   I decided to change that.    

01:00:30.918 --> 01:00:33.251
     The original plan was      
     to sabotage the ship,      

01:00:33.253 --> 01:00:37.621
   stage an alien attack        
   and make the world see that  
   space travel is dangerous    

01:00:37.623 --> 01:00:39.656
 and only a place for experts.  

01:00:39.658 --> 01:00:42.959
 And you had the perfect guests 
 to help you with your plan.    

01:00:42.961 --> 01:00:46.928
 Two veteran astronauts to make 
 the trip seem credible.        

01:00:46.930 --> 01:00:49.096
      And you had U-Boat,       

01:00:49.098 --> 01:00:51.998
 a superstar athlete            
 that would ensure              
 the whole world was watching.  

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:56.935
 And Ridley, the one person you 
 knew would confirm to the      
 world that aliens were real.   

01:00:56.937 --> 01:00:59.137
      Don't forget Clark.       

01:00:59.139 --> 01:01:01.939
       <i>Celebrity Heat</i> would     
      give you all the exposure 
      you could ever need,      

01:01:01.941 --> 01:01:04.107
  by ignoring the actual facts  

01:01:04.109 --> 01:01:06.409
      to get you                
      a sensational story.      

01:01:06.411 --> 01:01:08.177
        -Sorry, Clark.          
        -It's a living.         

01:01:09.279 --> 01:01:11.580
  You had it all figured out.   

01:01:11.582 --> 01:01:15.950
      Except I didn't count     
      on the greatest mystery   
      team being on board.      

01:01:15.952 --> 01:01:17.918
 That was just plain old luck.  

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:19.319
           Bad luck.            

01:01:19.321 --> 01:01:21.788
      I knew your snooping      
      would ruin my plans.      

01:01:21.790 --> 01:01:23.956
       I even tried to convince 
       you not to go.           

01:01:23.958 --> 01:01:29.327
    Well, Daphne,               
    your hair is so great,      
    I'd consider not going.     

01:01:29.329 --> 01:01:33.430
   Then, I switched your        
   scores, hoping it would      
   break up your happy team.    

01:01:33.432 --> 01:01:34.998
      And I guess               
      it did for a while.       

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:38.334
       Wait, so I didn't get    
       the highest score?       

01:01:38.336 --> 01:01:41.203
    (CHUCKLES WRYLY)            
    No, Daphne. Shaggy did!     

01:01:41.205 --> 01:01:42.437
         -What?                 
         -ALL: Shaggy?          

01:01:42.439 --> 01:01:44.972
   Like, dude, me? (CHUCKLES)   

01:01:44.974 --> 01:01:48.675
 I had to prevent you from      
 figuring out my plans so I     
 came up with a different one.  

01:01:48.677 --> 01:01:50.543
       A plan that meant        
       leaving you here.        

01:01:50.545 --> 01:01:54.046
 So we would never be able to   
 return to tell the real story. 

01:01:54.048 --> 01:01:56.548
    It was you that             
    sabotaged the satellite!    

01:01:56.550 --> 01:02:00.118
  Boy! Everything that happened 
  was perfectly calculated.     

01:02:00.120 --> 01:02:02.120
     And expertly executed.     

01:02:02.122 --> 01:02:06.123
    And you would have got      
    away with it too, if it     
    hadn't have been for me.    

01:02:06.125 --> 01:02:07.224
              You?              

01:02:08.626 --> 01:02:10.059
           Oh, right.           

01:02:10.061 --> 01:02:12.661
    I meant and you would have  
    gotten away with it too,    

01:02:12.663 --> 01:02:16.197
    if it wasn't for me         
    and these meddling kids.    

01:02:16.199 --> 01:02:18.332
    (CHUCKLES) "Would have"?    

01:02:18.334 --> 01:02:20.133
 Oh, I'm getting away with it.  

01:02:20.901 --> 01:02:22.134
         (DEVICE BEEPS)         

01:02:26.038 --> 01:02:28.172
     It's some sort of          
     invisible force field.     

01:02:28.174 --> 01:02:30.207
  Uh, it's called glass, Fred.  

01:02:30.209 --> 01:02:34.044
       An invisible force field 
       made out of glass!       

01:02:34.046 --> 01:02:36.046
           -Genius.             
           -(GROANS)            

01:02:36.048 --> 01:02:39.482
            -You're just going  
            to leave me here?   
            -And us.            

01:02:39.484 --> 01:02:43.084
    Oh, right. You're just      
       going to leave me        
    here with these people?     

01:02:43.086 --> 01:02:44.318
           Oh, yeah.            

01:02:44.320 --> 01:02:46.586
        And just to be certain  
        you never leave,        

01:02:46.588 --> 01:02:50.756
    I've planted thermal        
    charges like this one       
    throughout the complex.     

01:02:50.758 --> 01:02:52.591
     How many can there be?     

01:02:52.593 --> 01:02:54.893
           (BEEPING)            

01:03:01.366 --> 01:03:05.535
  So that's what that alien was 
  doing when Scoob and I went   
  outside for the drive.        

01:03:05.537 --> 01:03:08.237
      Shannon, name your price! 
      Anything!                 

01:03:08.239 --> 01:03:10.072
  A weekend in Paris with me!   

01:03:10.074 --> 01:03:12.106
    A signed portrait of me!    

01:03:14.375 --> 01:03:16.075
         (ALL EXCLAIM)          

01:03:16.077 --> 01:03:18.844
     You can't put a price      
     on this sort of fame.      

01:03:18.846 --> 01:03:23.715
   Besides, returning as a hero 
   will bring me all the money  
   I could ever want.           

01:03:23.717 --> 01:03:26.084
    Please don't hate me,       
    especially you, Daphne.     

01:03:27.086 --> 01:03:28.686
  (CLICKS TONGUE) Great hair.   

01:03:28.688 --> 01:03:30.287
           (LAUGHING)           

01:03:33.890 --> 01:03:35.190
           (BEEPING)            

01:03:42.597 --> 01:03:45.599
 -We've got to get out of here. 
 -How?                          

01:03:45.601 --> 01:03:48.401
              -She just left    
              on the only ship! 
              -No.              

01:03:48.403 --> 01:03:50.369
    It's not the only ship.     

01:03:53.973 --> 01:03:57.908
      RIDLEY:  <i>I got to hand</i>    
       <i>it to you. It looks just</i> 
       <i>like</i> Sly Star One.       

01:03:57.910 --> 01:04:00.410
 <i>But something feels different.</i> 

01:04:00.412 --> 01:04:02.545
         <i>I just can't put</i>       
         <i>my finger on it.</i>       

01:04:02.547 --> 01:04:05.114
    ZIP:  <i>You can't, 'cause</i>     
       <i>I'd say that pretty</i>      
     <i>much is the difference.</i>    

01:04:08.651 --> 01:04:10.618
   I can put my finger on it.   

01:04:11.252 --> 01:04:12.986
           Oh, right.           

01:04:12.988 --> 01:04:14.887
       It's really small.       

01:04:14.889 --> 01:04:16.321
     How are we all             
     going to fit in there?     

01:04:16.323 --> 01:04:17.822
      This isn't the ship.      

01:04:17.824 --> 01:04:19.657
      It's just the model.      

01:04:19.659 --> 01:04:21.125
         (DOOR OPENING)         

01:04:27.932 --> 01:04:30.133
 Oh, well, that's more like it. 

01:04:30.135 --> 01:04:31.834
        You built this?         

01:04:31.836 --> 01:04:35.170
      I did, with a little help 
      from the Sly bots.        

01:04:35.172 --> 01:04:38.106
     Well, why did              
     you keep it a secret?      

01:04:38.108 --> 01:04:44.011
 Well, actually you see, living 
 up here in the darkness,       
 all alone, it's been hard.     

01:04:44.013 --> 01:04:46.780
       I built this ship        
       so I could leave.        

01:04:46.782 --> 01:04:48.248
        But I couldn't.         

01:04:48.250 --> 01:04:50.183
    I knew how much             
    this place meant to you,    

01:04:50.185 --> 01:04:52.785
    how much you                
    needed me to stay here.     

01:04:52.787 --> 01:04:55.788
    But there were times        
    I thought about leaving.    

01:04:55.790 --> 01:04:59.257
  -About being...               
  -In the spotlight, like me?   

01:04:59.259 --> 01:05:00.458
             No...              

01:05:00.460 --> 01:05:02.693
  About being with my brother.  

01:05:04.996 --> 01:05:06.930
       I'm sorry, Hudson.       

01:05:06.932 --> 01:05:09.198
      I'm sorry for not         
      being here for you.       

01:05:14.771 --> 01:05:17.572
    Be sure to get              
    a close shot of my face.    

01:05:18.006 --> 01:05:19.139
              Sly!              

01:05:19.141 --> 01:05:21.274
      Sorry, it's a habit.      

01:05:21.276 --> 01:05:23.442
          (EXPLOSION)           

01:05:23.444 --> 01:05:26.144
      Shannon's explosives are  
      starting to go off!       

01:05:26.146 --> 01:05:27.278
      We better get going.      

01:05:28.980 --> 01:05:30.447
      Does your ship work?      

01:05:30.449 --> 01:05:32.315
  There's still some glitches   

01:05:32.317 --> 01:05:35.284
    but with some quick work,   
    she should be up            
    and running in no time.     

01:05:44.159 --> 01:05:45.559
           (GRUNTING)           

01:05:46.494 --> 01:05:47.894
       There's too many.        

01:05:47.896 --> 01:05:49.262
     This could take days.      

01:05:50.030 --> 01:05:51.830
      We don't have days!       

01:05:51.832 --> 01:05:54.165
     Gee, Daph, you think?      

01:05:54.167 --> 01:05:57.134
  Did you just do all that math 
  on your own or did your pal   
  Shannon help you?             

01:05:57.136 --> 01:05:59.369
     Oh, I'm sorry, Velma.      

01:05:59.371 --> 01:06:01.838
   So Shannon wasn't perfect.   

01:06:01.840 --> 01:06:06.141
   Perfect? Daphne, she's       
   a homicidal lunatic that's   
   about to blow up the moon!   

01:06:06.143 --> 01:06:08.510
  Oh, Velma, she's not going to 
  blow up the whole moon.       

01:06:08.512 --> 01:06:10.745
  Just, you know, part of it.   

01:06:10.747 --> 01:06:13.547
      And that's                
      supposed to be okay?      

01:06:13.549 --> 01:06:14.881
           Stop that!           

01:06:14.883 --> 01:06:16.749
       Stop! Stop! Stop!        

01:06:16.751 --> 01:06:18.917
   Stop it! Stop it! Stop it!   

01:06:18.919 --> 01:06:22.086
  For goodness sake,            
  we're all going to die        
  and all you can think about   

01:06:22.088 --> 01:06:25.255
 is arguing over who liked who! 

01:06:25.257 --> 01:06:26.589
         You're crazy!          

01:06:28.224 --> 01:06:30.525
  You're not a robot, are you?  

01:06:30.527 --> 01:06:31.726
             Nope.              

01:06:32.694 --> 01:06:35.662
 I'm an actor playing a robot.  

01:06:35.664 --> 01:06:38.331
       And if it wasn't for you 
       meddling kids...         

01:06:38.333 --> 01:06:39.699
    ALL: You would have         
    gotten away with it too.    

01:06:39.701 --> 01:06:40.866
       Yeah, yeah, yeah.        

01:06:40.868 --> 01:06:42.067
     Blah, blah, blupity...     

01:06:42.069 --> 01:06:43.835
          (STRAINING)           

01:06:46.872 --> 01:06:48.105
           (PANTING)            

01:06:48.107 --> 01:06:50.440
       It's no good.            
       They're too heavy.       

01:06:50.442 --> 01:06:52.508
   What the heck is in them?    

01:06:58.047 --> 01:06:59.547
        Wow! (LAUGHING)         

01:06:59.549 --> 01:07:01.515
         U-Boat snacks!         

01:07:01.517 --> 01:07:03.683
        A year's supply.        

01:07:03.685 --> 01:07:06.652
 -How in the world are we going 
 to get through all that?       
 -(MUNCHING)                    

01:07:10.724 --> 01:07:12.157
          Well, yeah.           

01:07:12.159 --> 01:07:14.559
     Like, time for the experts 
     to take over.              

01:07:14.561 --> 01:07:16.561
            -Right, Scooby-Doo? 
            -Uh-huh.            

01:07:27.973 --> 01:07:29.406
          (CHUCKLING)           

01:07:33.477 --> 01:07:35.511
     Caroline, about time.      

01:07:35.513 --> 01:07:37.913
        Help us move the last   
        of these boxes.         

01:07:37.915 --> 01:07:42.017
        That's not Caroline.    
        She's different.        

01:07:42.019 --> 01:07:45.953
   Oh, for Pete's sake, Ridley, 
   she's not different.         
   She's the same old... Oh!    

01:07:46.888 --> 01:07:48.054
           (SCREAMS)            

01:07:48.989 --> 01:07:50.222
       That is different.       

01:07:51.857 --> 01:07:53.290
              Run!              

01:07:55.192 --> 01:07:57.259
          (INAUDIBLE)           

01:08:00.997 --> 01:08:03.164
          RIDLEY: She's going   
          to kill us.           

01:08:03.166 --> 01:08:05.099
        U-Boat, come on!        

01:08:05.101 --> 01:08:07.768
   No, if she makes it through, 
   she'll crush the ship.       

01:08:07.770 --> 01:08:10.437
     I'll hold her off          
     while you guys fix         
     whatever needs fixing.     

01:08:10.439 --> 01:08:11.571
              Go!               

01:08:14.874 --> 01:08:15.974
              Go!               

01:08:23.881 --> 01:08:26.049
       Oh, she's been           
       idle for too long.       

01:08:26.051 --> 01:08:28.684
   -We're going to have to jump 
   her from the energy cell.    
   -We're on it.                

01:08:28.685 --> 01:08:29.917
        (BONES CRACKING)        

01:08:29.920 --> 01:08:31.286
        (YELLS) My back!        

01:08:31.287 --> 01:08:32.453
     My knees aren't            
     what they used to be.      

01:08:32.455 --> 01:08:34.087
        (BONES CRACKING)        

01:08:34.089 --> 01:08:36.188
        -Maybe we're getting    
        too old for this.       
        -No! You're not!        

01:08:38.890 --> 01:08:41.292
       Don't you get it?        

01:08:41.294 --> 01:08:44.895
  You guys are the reasons      
  why thousands, millions even, 
  want to become astronauts.    

01:08:44.897 --> 01:08:46.729
  Why I wanted to become one.   

01:08:46.732 --> 01:08:48.865
         You're the inspiration 
         for dreams             

01:08:48.867 --> 01:08:51.466
 and that sort of stuff         
 can never get old or obsolete. 

01:08:51.469 --> 01:08:55.270
  You're Zip Elvin and          
  Colt Steelcase, astronauts.   

01:08:55.272 --> 01:08:58.305
   You'll always be astronauts. 
   And how great is that?       

01:09:00.408 --> 01:09:01.642
     It's a three-man job.      

01:09:01.644 --> 01:09:03.210
        We'll need someone      
        to come with us.        

01:09:04.578 --> 01:09:07.714
  -Daphne...                    
  -No, no, Fred. We meant you!  

01:09:07.716 --> 01:09:09.314
            Oh. Me?             

01:09:09.816 --> 01:09:11.116
              Oh!               

01:09:12.984 --> 01:09:15.185
       Ugh! Dirty robot!        

01:09:18.957 --> 01:09:20.357
            (GROANS)            

01:09:33.937 --> 01:09:36.305
 Thanks, but aren't you scared? 

01:09:36.307 --> 01:09:39.474
      (CHUCKLING) Yeah,         
      like really scared.       

01:09:39.475 --> 01:09:43.176
       But like we said,        
       when we get scared,      
       we resort to food.       

01:09:43.179 --> 01:09:46.446
    That's how we deal with it. 
    Right, Scooby-Doo?          

01:09:46.448 --> 01:09:50.582
     Yeah, and if there's       
     one thing we love to do    
     besides eating food...     

01:09:52.785 --> 01:09:54.619
     It's playing with it.      

01:09:54.621 --> 01:09:56.020
          Food fight!           

01:09:59.624 --> 01:10:02.459
    It worked.                  
    The engines are primed.     

01:10:02.461 --> 01:10:04.527
  Hudson, ready when you are.   

01:10:04.529 --> 01:10:06.962
       Well done, guys.         
       Now get back here.       

01:10:06.964 --> 01:10:09.431
   Hudson, we have a problem.   

01:10:09.433 --> 01:10:12.033
       -What's wrong?           
       -What is it, Zip?        

01:10:12.035 --> 01:10:14.535
     -The fuel valve is broken. 
     -(ALARM BLARING)           

01:10:14.537 --> 01:10:17.137
   We gotta hold it on to keep  
   the power supply running.    

01:10:17.139 --> 01:10:19.772
   We'll have to ride it out of 
   the engine compartment.      

01:10:19.774 --> 01:10:22.441
         -Okay, I'll fly the... 
         -(THUDDING)            

01:10:22.443 --> 01:10:24.843
      He's out cold.            
      Who's going               
      to fly the ship now?      

01:10:24.845 --> 01:10:26.544
        I've got this...        

01:10:28.813 --> 01:10:30.280
         -Not to worry, I'll... 
         -(THUDDING)            

01:10:32.149 --> 01:10:34.049
     You can't be serious.      

01:10:41.190 --> 01:10:44.192
 Okay, looks like all that food 
 has made her sleepy.           

01:10:44.194 --> 01:10:45.459
     Let's get to the ship.     

01:10:50.297 --> 01:10:52.731
     -What happened?            
     -They got knocked out.     

01:10:52.733 --> 01:10:54.799
        Then who's gonna        
        fly this thing?         

01:10:54.801 --> 01:10:56.300
           -Don't worry, I...   
           -BOTH: No!           

01:10:56.302 --> 01:10:57.401
              Oh!               

01:10:59.003 --> 01:11:00.136
            (GROANS)            

01:11:00.138 --> 01:11:01.570
          (BOTH GASP)           

01:11:02.838 --> 01:11:04.638
    Don't worry. I got this.    

01:11:04.640 --> 01:11:06.039
           (GRUNTING)           

01:11:09.410 --> 01:11:11.677
      But they're               
      all wearing helmets.      

01:11:11.679 --> 01:11:13.679
    -COLT:  <i>What's the hold up?</i> 
    <i>-Uh...</i>                      

01:11:13.681 --> 01:11:16.181
 Everybody's been knocked out.  

01:11:16.183 --> 01:11:18.349
        There's nobody          
        to fly the ship!        

01:11:18.351 --> 01:11:21.051
    Yes, there is. Stand by.    

01:11:22.053 --> 01:11:24.154
       No! No way, Velma.       

01:11:24.156 --> 01:11:28.024
    I can't. You heard Shannon. 
    She faked the scores.       

01:11:28.026 --> 01:11:30.693
      Velma, I can't even drive 
      Fred's van.               

01:11:30.695 --> 01:11:32.661
     I just don't               
     have the right stuff.      

01:11:32.663 --> 01:11:34.029
          Yes, you do!          

01:11:34.031 --> 01:11:35.864
         You were on the bridge 
         with Shannon.          

01:11:35.866 --> 01:11:38.499
      You're the only one       
      that saw how              
      she flew this thing.      

01:11:38.501 --> 01:11:42.736
   Right now, you know          
   more than I do about this.   

01:11:42.738 --> 01:11:46.439
   Sure, Shannon might          
   have faked your score, but   
   it doesn't matter, Daphne.   

01:11:46.441 --> 01:11:48.441
  It's just a piece of paper.   

01:11:48.443 --> 01:11:52.344
    I don't need                
    a piece of paper to tell me 
    what I already know.        

01:11:52.346 --> 01:11:54.112
     That I believe in you.     

01:11:54.114 --> 01:11:57.148
 And that you can do anything   
 you put your mind to, Daphne.  

01:12:27.445 --> 01:12:31.381
       Wow! Looks like          
       a billion dollars        
       going up in smoke.       

01:12:31.383 --> 01:12:34.450
       Yeah, but think          
       of the publicity.        

01:12:39.922 --> 01:12:42.089
        Everyone, hold          
        on to something.        

01:12:42.091 --> 01:12:43.990
  This is going to get bumpy.   

01:12:55.101 --> 01:12:58.069
  Fred, we couldn't have had    
  a better team lead than you.  

01:12:58.071 --> 01:12:59.437
            Thanks.             

01:12:59.439 --> 01:13:01.238
       It was a real honor      
       working with you.        

01:13:02.640 --> 01:13:05.108
    We're about                 
    to enter the atmosphere.    

01:13:05.110 --> 01:13:06.676
        (ALL SCREAMING)         

01:13:10.280 --> 01:13:12.514
    MALE REPORTER:              
    Miss Lucas! Miss Lucas!     

01:13:12.516 --> 01:13:17.084
 And it was this terrible alien 
 that destroyed the station     
 and my friends.                

01:13:17.086 --> 01:13:18.351
           (SOBBING)            

01:13:18.353 --> 01:13:20.986
    Space is no place           
    for the average person.     

01:13:20.988 --> 01:13:24.756
   It's for trained astronauts, 
   like me.                     

01:13:24.758 --> 01:13:26.524
   -FRED: That's a great story. 
   -(GASPS)                     

01:13:35.132 --> 01:13:36.432
        If it were true.        

01:13:39.769 --> 01:13:42.337
         <i>And just to be certain</i> 
         <i>you never leave,</i>       

01:13:42.339 --> 01:13:46.107
   <i>I've planted thermal charges</i> 
   <i>like this one</i>                
   <i>throughout the complex.</i>      

01:13:46.109 --> 01:13:48.843
      <i>You can't put a price</i>     
      <i>on this sort of fame.</i>     

01:13:48.845 --> 01:13:53.613
   <i>Besides, returning as a hero</i> 
   <i>will bring me all the money</i>  
   <i>I could ever want.</i>           

01:13:53.615 --> 01:13:54.847
         (CROWD GASPS)          

01:13:54.849 --> 01:13:56.615
   (CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)   

01:13:57.817 --> 01:13:59.651
       She was the alien!       

01:13:59.653 --> 01:14:01.219
         A fake alien!          

01:14:05.490 --> 01:14:09.826
 Sly was right.                 
 Space travel is for everyone!  

01:14:09.828 --> 01:14:14.530
  Sure, it takes training,      
  but maybe it all starts       
  with an adventurous spirit,   

01:14:14.532 --> 01:14:18.066
         an imaginative mind,   
         a brave heart,         

01:14:18.068 --> 01:14:21.502
   -and good old-fashioned...   
   -Money, tons of the stuff!   

01:14:21.504 --> 01:14:23.737
            -Sly, please!       
            -Sorry.             

01:14:23.739 --> 01:14:26.840
    And good                    
    old-fashioned curiosity.    

01:14:26.842 --> 01:14:28.575
  Who knows what's out there?   

01:14:28.577 --> 01:14:31.844
     But isn't that             
     the very reason to go?     

01:14:31.846 --> 01:14:33.645
        (CROWD CHEERING)        

01:14:35.314 --> 01:14:36.913
        (CROWD JEERING)         

01:14:39.650 --> 01:14:43.185
      Like, dude,               
      it was real swell         
      meeting you, U-Boat.      

01:14:43.187 --> 01:14:45.754
       Yeah! Yeah! Swell!       

01:14:45.756 --> 01:14:49.356
      Shaggy, Scooby,           
      it was a real blast!      

01:14:49.358 --> 01:14:50.590
           Come here.           

01:14:50.592 --> 01:14:52.825
           (CHOKING)            

01:14:52.827 --> 01:14:55.027
       Velma, I'm sorry.        

01:14:55.029 --> 01:14:58.196
  I should have seen            
  that Shannon                  
  wasn't really a true friend,  

01:14:58.198 --> 01:15:00.698
       and that you were always 
       my best friend.          

01:15:00.700 --> 01:15:05.235
  -Aw. Thanks, Daphne!          
  Maybe you and...              
  -(CAMERA SHUTTERS CLICKING)   

01:15:05.237 --> 01:15:06.836
    REPORTER: Tell us           
    about your trip, Daphne.    

01:15:06.838 --> 01:15:09.205
  REPORTER 2:                   
  How do you keep your hair...  

01:15:09.207 --> 01:15:11.607
  PHOTOGRAPHER: Daphne,         
  over here! I need some shots  
  of the hair. It's beautiful!  

01:15:12.375 --> 01:15:14.075
            My hair?            

01:15:14.077 --> 01:15:17.445
    There are far more          
    important things            
    to talk about than hair.    

01:15:17.447 --> 01:15:20.047
  Like friendship and support.  

01:15:20.049 --> 01:15:22.416
   Now that's worth a story.    

01:15:22.418 --> 01:15:23.417
     (REPORTERS CLAMORING)      

01:15:27.288 --> 01:15:30.890
      So, I guess there are     
      no aliens after all.      

01:15:30.892 --> 01:15:33.859
       Oh, I wouldn't say that, 
       Ridley.                  

01:15:33.861 --> 01:15:37.262
  Space is too big.             
  Who knows what's out there?   

01:15:38.497 --> 01:15:40.564
        You must have been      
        lonely up there.        

01:15:40.566 --> 01:15:44.968
    No less lonely than someone 
    who believes in something   
    when nobody else does.      

01:15:50.674 --> 01:15:52.074
          (EXPLOSION)           

01:15:52.076 --> 01:15:54.376
      Uh, looks like            
      your ship is ruined.      

01:15:54.378 --> 01:15:58.212
   Yes, but it wouldn't         
   take me long                 
   to have her back in shape.   

01:15:58.214 --> 01:16:00.147
       And maybe if, uh,        

01:16:00.149 --> 01:16:02.549
  somebody would come with me,  

01:16:02.551 --> 01:16:04.584
      I wouldn't mind           
      going back up there.      

01:16:04.586 --> 01:16:06.552
    See what we might find.     

01:16:06.554 --> 01:16:10.322
    You mean a copasetic        
    prime directive involving   
    a dual core system drive    

01:16:10.324 --> 01:16:14.558
   with a high probability      
   of some elementary binary    
   codex and interface time?    

01:16:14.560 --> 01:16:16.459
     I couldn't have            
     said it better myself.     

01:16:24.934 --> 01:16:27.869
     -(ENGINE STARTING)         
     -FRED: Easy, just let      
     the clutch out, easy!      

01:16:27.871 --> 01:16:30.271
       -(GRUNTS)                
       -DAPHNE: Jeepers!        

01:16:30.273 --> 01:16:32.006
       I'm trying, Fred.        

01:16:32.008 --> 01:16:34.008
        Something must be wrong 
        with the pedal.         

01:16:34.010 --> 01:16:36.844
          -Okay, calm down.     
          -I am calm!           

01:16:36.846 --> 01:16:41.214
 -Daph, why don't you try...    
 -Velma, why don't you try      
 not being a back seat driver!  

01:16:41.216 --> 01:16:43.349
       I flew a spaceship       
       for goodness sake!       

01:16:43.351 --> 01:16:45.451
      I think I can handle      
      the Mystery Machine.      

01:16:45.453 --> 01:16:47.986
      Okay, okay.               
      Just trying to help.      

01:16:48.721 --> 01:16:50.788
           Go ahead.            

01:16:50.790 --> 01:16:52.689
          FRED: Easy. Easy!     
          VELMA: Whoa!          

01:16:52.691 --> 01:16:54.057
           ALL: Whoa!           

01:16:54.059 --> 01:16:56.992
 SCOOBY-DOO: Scooby-Dooby-Doo!  

01:16:57.893 --> 01:16:59.260
          (WHIMPERING)          

